{"title_page": "TCN Protocol", "text_new": "{{Infobox protocol\n| name        = Temporary Contact Numbers Protocol\n| image       = TCN_Protocol_Logo.png\n| caption     = \n| developer   = TCN Coalition\n| introdate   = {{Start date|2020|04|01}}<ref name=\"initial-commit\">{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/TCNCoalition/TCN/commit/1b68b920db1fb42709c7c8eb28c3d5e10c76fc3c|title=Initial commit \u00b7 TCNCoalition/TCN@1b68b92|website=GitHub|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n| industry    = [[Digital contact tracing]]\n| range       = ~{{convert|10|m|ft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.nordicsemi.com/getconnected/things-you-should-know-about-bluetooth-range|title=Things You Should Know About Bluetooth Range|last=Spon\u00e5s|first=Jon Gunnar|website=blog.nordicsemi.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n| newer       = <!--superseded by which protocol-->\n| website     = https://tcn-coalition.org/\n}}\nThe '''Temporary Contact Numbers Protocol''', or '''TCN Protocol''', is an [[open source]], [[Decentralised system|decentralized]], privacy focused [[contact tracing]] protocol developed by the TCN Coalition in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2020/04/13/what-privacy-preserving-coronavirus-tracing-apps-need-to-succeed/|title=What privacy-preserving coronavirus tracing apps need to succeed|date=2020-04-13|website=VentureBeat|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/1838625/how-bluetooth-could-power-a-global-experiment-in-contact-tracing/|title=How Bluetooth could bring digital contact tracing for Covid-19 to billions|last=Shendruk|first=Amrita Khalid, Amanda|website=Quartz|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.stanford.edu/2020/04/09/stanford-researchers-help-develop-privacy-focused-coronavirus-alert-app/|title=Stanford researchers help develop privacy-focused coronavirus alert app|last=University|first=Stanford|date=2020-04-09|website=Stanford News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The protocol, like [[BlueTrace]] and the [[Google / Apple contact tracing project]], use [[Bluetooth Low Energy]] to track and log encounters with other users.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://bluetrace.io/static/bluetrace_whitepaper-938063656596c104632def383eb33b3c.pdf|title=BlueTrace: A privacy-preserving protocol for community-driven contact tracing across borders|last=Jason Bay, Joel Kek, Alvin Tan, Chai Sheng Hau, Lai Yongquan, Janice Tan, Tang Anh Quy|first=|date=|website=Government Technology Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/apple-google-contact-tracing-strengths-weaknesses/|title=Is Apple and Google's Covid-19 Contact Tracing a Privacy Risk?|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thecurrencyanalytics.com/13404/zcash-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app-on-blockchain-the-temporary-contact-number-tcn-coalition/|title=ZCash Privacy Preserving Contact Tracing App on Blockchain the Temporary Contact Number TCN Coalition|date=2020-04-12|website=Cryptocurrency News - TCAT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> The major distinction between TCN and protocols like BlueTrace is the fact the central reporting server never has access to contact logs nor is it responsible for processing and informing clients of contact.<ref name=\":2\">{{Citation|title=TCNCoalition/TCN|date=2020-04-18|url=https://github.com/TCNCoalition/TCN|publisher=TCN Coalition|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pact.mit.edu/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/The-PACT-protocol-specification-ver-0.1.pdf|title=The PACT protocol specification|last=|first=|date=|website=PACT MIT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> Because contact logs are never transmitted to third parties, it has major privacy benefits over approaches like the one used in BlueTrace.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theinternetofthings.eu/aisshwarya-tiwar-covid-19-zcash-zec-and-tcn-developing-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app|title=Aisshwarya Tiwar: COVID-19: Zcash (ZEC) and TCN Developing Privacy-Preserving Contact Tracing App {{!}} IoT Council |last=|first=|date=|website=www.theinternetofthings.eu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://btcmanager.com/covid-19-zcash-zec-tcn-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app/|title=COVID-19: Zcash (ZEC) and TCN Developing Privacy-Preserving Contact Tracing App {{!}} BTCMANAGER|last=|first=|date=2020-04-12|website=btcmanager|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Nabben|first=Kelsie|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/340772290_Trustless_Approaches_to_Digital_Infrastructure_in_the_Crisis_of_COVID-19|title=Trustless Approaches to Digital Infrastructure in the Crisis of COVID-19|date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://arxiv.org/pdf/2004.07717.pdf|title=Digital Ariadne: Citizen Empowerment for Epidemic Control|publisher=|year=2020|isbn=|location=|pages=|authors=Lorenz Cuno Klopfenstein, Saverio Delpriori, Gian Marco Di Francesco, Riccardo Maldini, Brendan Dominic Paolini, Alessandro Bogliolo}}</ref> This approach however, by its very nature, does not allow for human-in-the-loop reporting, potentially leading to false positives.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|p. 6}} \n\nThe TCN protocol received notoriety as one of the first widely released digital contact tracing protocols<ref name=\"initial-commit\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techxplore.com/news/2020-04-stanford-privacy-focused-coronavirus-app.html|title=Stanford researchers help develop privacy-focused coronavirus alert app|website=techxplore.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.gatech.edu/2020/04/14/will-smartphones-help-us-keep-covid-19-under-control|title=Will Smartphones Help Us Keep COVID-19 Under Control?|website=www.news.gatech.edu|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> alongside BlueTrace,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/covid19-trace-together-mobile-app-contact-tracing-coronavirus-12560616|title=Singapore launches TraceTogether mobile app to boost COVID-19 contact tracing efforts|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> the Google/Apple project, and the [[Pan-European Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing]] (PEPP-PT) project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insideprivacy.com/covid-19/covid-19-apps-and-websites-the-pan-european-privacy-preserving-proximity-tracing-initiative-and-guidance-by-supervisory-authorities/|title=COVID-19 Apps and Websites - The \u201cPan-European Privacy Preserving Proximity Tracing Initiative\u201d and Guidance by Supervisory Authorities|date=2020-04-02|website=Inside Privacy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zfnd.org/blog/private-contact-tracing-protocols-compared/|title=Private Contact Tracing Protocols Compared: DP-3T and CEN|last=Valence|first=Henry de|website=The Zcash Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> It also stood out for it's incorporation of [[blockchain]] technology,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thecurrencyanalytics.com/13404/zcash-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app-on-blockchain-the-temporary-contact-number-tcn-coalition/|title=ZCash Privacy Preserving Contact Tracing App on Blockchain the Temporary Contact Number TCN Coalition|date=2020-04-12|website=Cryptocurrency News - TCAT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cryptopolitan.com/contact-tracing-app-blockchain-based-zcash/|title=Contact tracing app on the Zcash blockchain platform underway|website=Cryptopolitan|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> and it's similarity to the later released Google/Apple project.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=22834959|title=Apple and Google partner on Covid-19 contact tracing technology {{!}} Hacker News|website=news.ycombinator.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lightbluetouchpaper.org/2020/04/12/contact-tracing-in-the-real-world/|title=Contact Tracing in the Real World {{!}} Light Blue Touchpaper|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nOn {{Date|2020-04-21|}}, the protocol, alongside [[Decentralized Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing|DP-3T]] and the [[Privacy Automated Contact Tracing]] protocol, appeared in a joint statement signed by hundreds of academics to recommend a more decentralized approach to digital contact tracing than the predominant PEPP-PT protocol.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ledgerinsights.com/eu-parliament-covid-19-contact-tracing-decentralized/|title=EU parliament demands COVID-19 contact tracing be decentralized. Academics concerned re privacy|last=Insights|first=Ledger|date=2020-04-21|website=Ledger Insights - enterprise blockchain|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1OQg2dxPu-x-RZzETlpV3lFa259Nrpk1J/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=Joint Statement.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Docs|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.org/details/joint-statement-digital-contact-tracing|archive-date=2020-04-22|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\nThe TCN protocol works off the basis of Temporary Contact Numbers (TCN), semi-random identifiers derived from a seed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lucumr.pocoo.org/2020/4/9/tcn-contact-tracing/|title=Temporary Contact Number based Contact Tracing|website=lucumr.pocoo.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> When two clients encounter each other, a unique TCN is generated, exchanged, and then locally stored in a contact log.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ncase.me/contact-tracing/|title=Protecting Lives & Liberty: How Contact Tracing Can Foil COVID-19 & Big Brother|website=ncase.me|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Then, once a user tests positive for infection, a report is sent to a central server. Each client on the network then collects the reports from the server and independently checks their local contact logs for a TCN contained in the report. If a matching TCN is found, then the user has come in close contact with an infected patient, and is warned by the client. Since each device locally verifies contact logs, and thus contact logs are never transmitted to third parties, the central reporting server cannot by itself ascertain the identity or contact log of any client in the network. This is in contrast to competing protocols like BlueTrace, where the central reporting server receives and processes client contact logs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@frankvolkel/tracetogether-under-the-hood-7d5e509aeb5d|title=TraceTogether: under the hood|last=Liauw|first=\ud83c\uddf8\ud83c\uddec Frank|date=2020-04-09|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n== Temporary contact numbers ==\nThe entire protocol is based on the principle of ''temporary contact numbers'' (TCN), a unique and anonymous 128-bit identifier generated deterministically from a seed value on a client device. TCNs are used to identify people with which a user has come in contact, and the seed is used to compactly report infection to a central reporting server. TCN reports are authenticated to be genuine by a secret held only by the client.\n\n=== Generation ===\n\nTo generate a TCN, first a ''report authorization key'' (RAK) and ''report verification key'' (RVK) are created as the signing and verification keys of a signature scheme (RAK-RVK pair). In the reference implementation this pair is created using the [[Ed25519]] signature scheme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/TCNCoalition/TCN/blob/main/src/keys.rs|title=TCNCoalition/TCN/src/keys.rs|last=|first=|date=|website=GitHub|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>{{Rp|line. 13}} Then, using the RAK an initial ''temporary contact key'' (TCK) is generated using the algorithm <math>\ntck_{0} = H\\_tck(rak)\n</math>, where <math>\nH\\_tck()\n</math> is the [[SHA-2|SHA-256]] [[hash function]] as <math>\nH\\_tck(s) = SHA256(\\text{b'H}\\_\\text{TCK'}||s)\n</math>. This TCK is not used to generate any TCNs, but is used in the next TCK; where all future TCKs are calculated using the algorithm <math>\ntck_{i} = H\\_tck(rvk || tck_{i-1})\n</math>. A 128 bit TCN is then generated from a given TCK using the algorithm <math>\ntcn_{i>0} = H\\_tcn(le\\_u16(i) || tck_{i})\n</math>, where  <math>\nle\\_u16()\n</math> formats a supplied number as a [[little endian]] unsigned 2 byte integer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.rs/nom/2.2.1/nom/fn.le_u16.html|title=nom::le_u16 - Rust|website=docs.rs|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> and <math>\nH\\_tcn()\n</math> is the SHA-256 hash function as <math>\nH\\_tcn(s) = SHA256(\\text{b'H}\\_\\text{TCN'}||s)[0:128]\n</math>. The following diagram demonstrates the key derivation process:[[File:TCN_Protocol_Key_Generation.svg|center]]TCNs are unique to each device encounter, and RAK-RVK pairs are cycled at regular intervals to allow a client to report only specific periods of contact. \n\n=== Reporting ===\nWhen a client wishes to submit a report for the TCN indicies <math>\ns > 0\n</math> to <math>\ne\n</math>, it structures the report as <math>\nreport = rvk || tck_{s - 1} || le\\_u16(s) || le\\_u16(e) || memo\n</math>. A signature is then calculated using the RAK, and it is transmitted to the server as <math>\ns\\_report = report||sig\n</math>.\n\nBecause any given TCK can only be used to derive an equal or higher indexed TCNs, by submitting <math>\ntck_{s-1}\n</math> no encounters prior to <math>\ntcn_{s-1}\n</math> can be calculated. However there is no upper limit to encounters calculated using the same RAK-RVK pair, which is why they are cycled often. To prevent clients calculating unused TCNs, <math>\ne\n</math> indicates the last TCN index generated with the given RVK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/TCNCoalition/tcn-client-android/blob/develop/tcn-client-android/src/main/java/org/tcncoalition/tcnclient/TcnKeys.kt|title=TCNCoalition/tcn-client-android/src/main/java/org/tcncoalition/tcnclient/TcnKeys.kt|last=|first=|date=|website=GitHub|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>{{Rp|lines. 49-61}} Additionally, since the RVK is used to calculate a TCK, and <math>\ntck_{s-1}\n</math> is provided, no valid TCNs in the reporting period can be derived from an illegitimate report. The only correct TCN calculable from a mismatched RVK and <math>\ntck_{s-1}\n</math> is <math>\ntcn_{s-1}\n</math>, the TCN before the start of the reporting period.\n\nOnce a report is received, clients individually recalculate TCKs and TCNs for a given period using the original algorithms:<math display=\"block\">\n\\begin{array}{lcr}\ntck_s = H\\_tck(rvk || tck_{s-1})\\\\\ntcn_{s} = H\\_tcn(le\\_u16(s) || tck_{s})\\\\\ntck_{s+1} = H\\_tck(rvk || tck_{s})\\\\\ntcn_{s+1} = H\\_tcn(le\\_u16(s+1) || tck_{s+1})\\\\\n...\\\\\ntck_{e} = H\\_tck(rvk || tck_{e-1})\\\\\ntcn_{e} = H\\_tcn(le\\_u16(e) || tck_{e})\n\\end{array}\n</math>This is used by client devices to check their local contact logs for potential encounters with the infected patient, but has the dual benefit of verifying reports since false reports will never produce matching TCNs.\n\n=== Memo ===\nIn the report structure, the memo is a space for freeform messages that differ between TCN implementations. The section is between 2 and 257 bytes, and made up of a tag identifying the specific implementation, as well as a data and data length pair. It is formatted as  <math>\nmemo = tag || len(data) || data\n</math>. The data is standardized for different tags, and can be as follows:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Tag\n!Data standard\n|-\n|{{Code|code=0x0}}\n|[[CoEpi]] symptom report v1\n|-\n|{{Code|code=0x1}}\n|[[CovidWatch]] test result v1\n|-\n|{{Code|code=0x2-0xfe}}\n|Allocated for future official TCN apps or versions\n|-\n|{{Code|code=0xff}}\n|Reserved (can be used to add more than 256 types later)\n|}\n\n== Technical specification ==\nThe protocol can be divided into two responsibilities: an encounter between two devices running TCN apps, and the notification of potential infection to users that came in contact with a patient. For the purposes of this specification, these areas are named the ''encounter handshake'', and ''infection reporting''. The ''encounter handshake'' runs on Bluetooth LE and defines how two devices acknowledge each other's presence. The ''infection reporting'' is built on [[Hypertext Transfer Protocol|HTTPS]] and defines how infection notices are distributed among clients.\n\n=== Encounter handshake ===\nWhen two devices come within range of each other, they exchange a handshake containing TCNs. In order to achieve this the encounter handshake operates in two modes (both with two sub-modes), broadcast oriented and connection oriented. Broadcast oriented operates using the modes broadcaster and observer, while connection oriented operates using peripheral and central. The two modes are used to circumvent certain device limitations, particularly in regard to iOS restrictions in place before version 13.4.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/iOSBeta/comments/fcww2x/feature_ios_134_beta_enables_ble_long_range/|title=r/iOSBeta - [Feature] IOS 13.4 beta enables BLE long range support (iPhone 11/11 Pro only)|website=reddit|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> In both modes the protocol is identified with the 16 bit [[Universally unique identifier|UUID]] {{Code|code=0xC019}}.\n\nIn broadcast mode, a broadcaster advertises a 16-byte TCN using the service data field of the advertisement data. The observer reads the TCN from this field. In connection-oriented mode, the peripheral advertises using the UUID. The service exposes a read and writeable packet for sharing TCNs. After sharing a TCN, the central disconnects from the peripheral.\n\n=== Infection reporting ===\nWhen a user tests positive for infection, they upload a signed report allowing the past 14 days of encounters to be calculated to a central server. On a regular basis, client devices download reports from the server and check their local contact logs using the verification algorithm. If there is a matching record, the app notifies the user to potential infection.\n\n== TCN Coalition ==\nOn 5 April 2020, the global [[TCN Coalition]] was founded by groups that had coalesced around what was essentially the same approach and largely overlapping protocols, with the goal to reduce fragmentation, and enable global interoperability of tracing and alerting apps, a key aspect of achieving widespread adoption.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://tcn-coalition.org/|title=TCN Coalition \u00b7 A Global Coalition for Privacy-First Digital Contact Tracing Protocols to Fight COVID-19|website=tcn-coalition.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The TCN Coalition also helped establish the [[Data Rights for Digital Contact Tracing and Alerting]] framework, which functions as a bill of rights for users of such apps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dcta-datarights.com/|title=Data Rights for Digital Contact Tracing and Alerting \u00b7 Overview|last=Reed <questions@dcta-datarights.org>|first=Harper|website=dcta-datarights.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nCurrently the protocol is currently used by TCN Coalition members [[CoEpi]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miragenews.com/will-smartphones-help-us-keep-covid-19-under-control/,%20https://www.miragenews.com/will-smartphones-help-us-keep-covid-19-under-control|title=Will Smartphones Help Us Keep COVID-19 Under Control? {{!}} Mirage News|last=News|first=Mirage|date=2020-04-15|website=www.miragenews.com|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Co-Epi/app-android|date=2020-04-19|url=https://github.com/Co-Epi/app-android|publisher=CoEpi|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> and [[CovidWatch]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.covid-watch.org/|title=Covid Watch|website=www.covid-watch.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> and was likely a source of inspiration for the similar [[Google / Apple contact tracing project]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://covid-watch.org/press_releases/google_apple_press_release|title=Covid Watch Celebrates Apple and Google\u2019s COVID-19 Contact Tracing Announcement|last=|first=|date=|website=www.covid-watch.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[BlueTrace]]\n* [[Google / Apple contact tracing project]]\n*[[Pan-European Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing]]\n\n== References ==\n\n<references />{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}{{FOSS}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://tcn-coalition.org/ TCN Coalition]\n* [https://github.com/TCNCoalition/TCN Specification and reference implementation]\n\n[[Category:Application layer protocols]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2020]]\n[[Category:Software associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Bluetooth software]]\n[[Category:Medical software]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:IOS software]]\n[[Category:2020 software]]\n[[Category:Software using the MIT license]]\n[[Category:Digital contact tracing protocols]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox protocol\n| name        = Temporary Contact Numbers Protocol\n| image       = TCN_Protocol_Logo.png\n| caption     = \n| developer   = TCN Coalition\n| introdate   = {{Start date|2020|04|01}}<ref name=\"initial-commit\">{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/TCNCoalition/TCN/commit/1b68b920db1fb42709c7c8eb28c3d5e10c76fc3c|title=Initial commit \u00b7 TCNCoalition/TCN@1b68b92|website=GitHub|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n| industry    = [[Digital contact tracing]]\n| range       = ~{{convert|10|m|ft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.nordicsemi.com/getconnected/things-you-should-know-about-bluetooth-range|title=Things You Should Know About Bluetooth Range|last=Spon\u00e5s|first=Jon Gunnar|website=blog.nordicsemi.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n| newer       = <!--superseded by which protocol-->\n| website     = https://tcn-coalition.org/\n}}\nThe '''Temporary Contact Numbers Protocol''', or '''TCN Protocol''', is an [[open source]], [[Decentralised system|decentralized]], privacy focused [[contact tracing]] protocol developed by the TCN Coalition in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2020/04/13/what-privacy-preserving-coronavirus-tracing-apps-need-to-succeed/|title=What privacy-preserving coronavirus tracing apps need to succeed|date=2020-04-13|website=VentureBeat|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/1838625/how-bluetooth-could-power-a-global-experiment-in-contact-tracing/|title=How Bluetooth could bring digital contact tracing for Covid-19 to billions|last=Shendruk|first=Amrita Khalid, Amanda|website=Quartz|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.stanford.edu/2020/04/09/stanford-researchers-help-develop-privacy-focused-coronavirus-alert-app/|title=Stanford researchers help develop privacy-focused coronavirus alert app|last=University|first=Stanford|date=2020-04-09|website=Stanford News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The protocol, like [[BlueTrace]] and the [[Google / Apple contact tracing project]], use [[Bluetooth Low Energy]] to track and log encounters with other users.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://bluetrace.io/static/bluetrace_whitepaper-938063656596c104632def383eb33b3c.pdf|title=BlueTrace: A privacy-preserving protocol for community-driven contact tracing across borders|last=Jason Bay, Joel Kek, Alvin Tan, Chai Sheng Hau, Lai Yongquan, Janice Tan, Tang Anh Quy|first=|date=|website=Government Technology Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/apple-google-contact-tracing-strengths-weaknesses/|title=Is Apple and Google's Covid-19 Contact Tracing a Privacy Risk?|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thecurrencyanalytics.com/13404/zcash-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app-on-blockchain-the-temporary-contact-number-tcn-coalition/|title=ZCash Privacy Preserving Contact Tracing App on Blockchain the Temporary Contact Number TCN Coalition|date=2020-04-12|website=Cryptocurrency News - TCAT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> The major distinction between TCN and protocols like BlueTrace is the fact the central reporting server never has access to contact logs nor is it responsible for processing and informing clients of contact.<ref name=\":2\">{{Citation|title=TCNCoalition/TCN|date=2020-04-18|url=https://github.com/TCNCoalition/TCN|publisher=TCN Coalition|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pact.mit.edu/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/The-PACT-protocol-specification-ver-0.1.pdf|title=The PACT protocol specification|last=|first=|date=|website=PACT MIT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> Because contact logs are never transmitted to third parties, it has major privacy benefits over approaches like the one used in BlueTrace.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theinternetofthings.eu/aisshwarya-tiwar-covid-19-zcash-zec-and-tcn-developing-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app|title=Aisshwarya Tiwar: COVID-19: Zcash (ZEC) and TCN Developing Privacy-Preserving Contact Tracing App {{!}} IoT Council |last=|first=|date=|website=www.theinternetofthings.eu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://btcmanager.com/covid-19-zcash-zec-tcn-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app/|title=COVID-19: Zcash (ZEC) and TCN Developing Privacy-Preserving Contact Tracing App {{!}} BTCMANAGER|last=|first=|date=2020-04-12|website=btcmanager|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Nabben|first=Kelsie|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/340772290_Trustless_Approaches_to_Digital_Infrastructure_in_the_Crisis_of_COVID-19|title=Trustless Approaches to Digital Infrastructure in the Crisis of COVID-19|date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://arxiv.org/pdf/2004.07717.pdf|title=Digital Ariadne: Citizen Empowerment for Epidemic Control|publisher=|year=2020|isbn=|location=|pages=|authors=Lorenz Cuno Klopfenstein, Saverio Delpriori, Gian Marco Di Francesco, Riccardo Maldini, Brendan Dominic Paolini, Alessandro Bogliolo}}</ref> This approach however, by its very nature, does not allow for human-in-the-loop reporting, potentially leading to false positives.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|p. 6}} \n\nThe TCN protocol received notoriety as one of the first widely released digital contact tracing protocols<ref name=\"initial-commit\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techxplore.com/news/2020-04-stanford-privacy-focused-coronavirus-app.html|title=Stanford researchers help develop privacy-focused coronavirus alert app|website=techxplore.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.gatech.edu/2020/04/14/will-smartphones-help-us-keep-covid-19-under-control|title=Will Smartphones Help Us Keep COVID-19 Under Control?|website=www.news.gatech.edu|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> alongside BlueTrace,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/covid19-trace-together-mobile-app-contact-tracing-coronavirus-12560616|title=Singapore launches TraceTogether mobile app to boost COVID-19 contact tracing efforts|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> the Google/Apple project, and the [[Pan-European Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing]] (PEPP-PT) project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insideprivacy.com/covid-19/covid-19-apps-and-websites-the-pan-european-privacy-preserving-proximity-tracing-initiative-and-guidance-by-supervisory-authorities/|title=COVID-19 Apps and Websites - The \u201cPan-European Privacy Preserving Proximity Tracing Initiative\u201d and Guidance by Supervisory Authorities|date=2020-04-02|website=Inside Privacy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zfnd.org/blog/private-contact-tracing-protocols-compared/|title=Private Contact Tracing Protocols Compared: DP-3T and CEN|last=Valence|first=Henry de|website=The Zcash Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> It also stood out for it's incorporation of [[Blockchain]] technology,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thecurrencyanalytics.com/13404/zcash-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app-on-blockchain-the-temporary-contact-number-tcn-coalition/|title=ZCash Privacy Preserving Contact Tracing App on Blockchain the Temporary Contact Number TCN Coalition|date=2020-04-12|website=Cryptocurrency News - TCAT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cryptopolitan.com/contact-tracing-app-blockchain-based-zcash/|title=Contact tracing app on the Zcash blockchain platform underway|website=Cryptopolitan|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> and it's similarity to the later released Google/Apple project.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=22834959|title=Apple and Google partner on Covid-19 contact tracing technology {{!}} Hacker News|website=news.ycombinator.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lightbluetouchpaper.org/2020/04/12/contact-tracing-in-the-real-world/|title=Contact Tracing in the Real World {{!}} Light Blue Touchpaper|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nOn {{Date|2020-04-21|}}, the protocol, alongside [[Decentralized Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing|DP-3T]] and the [[Privacy Automated Contact Tracing]] protocol, appeared in a joint statement signed by hundreds of academics to recommend a more decentralized approach to digital contact tracing than the predominant PEPP-PT protocol.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ledgerinsights.com/eu-parliament-covid-19-contact-tracing-decentralized/|title=EU parliament demands COVID-19 contact tracing be decentralized. Academics concerned re privacy|last=Insights|first=Ledger|date=2020-04-21|website=Ledger Insights - enterprise blockchain|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1OQg2dxPu-x-RZzETlpV3lFa259Nrpk1J/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=Joint Statement.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Docs|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.org/details/joint-statement-digital-contact-tracing|archive-date=2020-04-22|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\nThe TCN protocol works off the basis of Temporary Contact Numbers (TCN), semi-random identifiers derived from a seed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lucumr.pocoo.org/2020/4/9/tcn-contact-tracing/|title=Temporary Contact Number based Contact Tracing|website=lucumr.pocoo.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> When two clients encounter each other, a unique TCN is generated, exchanged, and then locally stored in a contact log.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ncase.me/contact-tracing/|title=Protecting Lives & Liberty: How Contact Tracing Can Foil COVID-19 & Big Brother|website=ncase.me|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Then, once a user tests positive for infection, a report is sent to a central server. Each client on the network then collects the reports from the server and independently checks their local contact logs for a TCN contained in the report. If a matching TCN is found, then the user has come in close contact with an infected patient, and is warned by the client. Since each device locally verifies contact logs, and thus contact logs are never transmitted to third parties, the central reporting server cannot by itself ascertain the identity or contact log of any client in the network. This is in contrast to competing protocols like BlueTrace, where the central reporting server receives and processes client contact logs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@frankvolkel/tracetogether-under-the-hood-7d5e509aeb5d|title=TraceTogether: under the hood|last=Liauw|first=\ud83c\uddf8\ud83c\uddec Frank|date=2020-04-09|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n== Temporary Contact Numbers ==\nThe entire protocol is based on the principle of Temporary Contact Numbers (TCN), a unique and anonymous 128 bit identifier generated deterministically from a seed value on a client device. TCNs are used to identify people with which a user has come in contact, and the seed is used to compactly report infection to a central reporting server. TCN reports are authenticated to be genuine by a secret held only by the client.\n\n=== Generation ===\n\nTo generate a TCN, first a ''report authorization key'' (RAK) and ''report verification key'' (RVK) are created as the signing and verification keys of a signature scheme (RAK-RVK pair). In the reference implementation this pair is created using the [[Ed25519]] signature scheme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/TCNCoalition/TCN/blob/main/src/keys.rs|title=TCNCoalition/TCN/src/keys.rs|last=|first=|date=|website=GitHub|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>{{Rp|line. 13}} Then, using the RAK an initial ''temporary contact key'' (TCK) is generated using the algorithm <math>\ntck_{0} = H\\_tck(rak)\n</math>, where <math>\nH\\_tck()\n</math> is the [[SHA-2|SHA-256]] [[hash function]] as <math>\nH\\_tck(s) = SHA256(\\text{b'H}\\_\\text{TCK'}||s)\n</math>. This TCK is not used to generate any TCNs, but is used in the next TCK; where all future TCKs are calculated using the algorithm <math>\ntck_{i} = H\\_tck(rvk || tck_{i-1})\n</math>. A 128 bit TCN is then generated from a given TCK using the algorithm <math>\ntcn_{i>0} = H\\_tcn(le\\_u16(i) || tck_{i})\n</math>, where  <math>\nle\\_u16()\n</math> formats a supplied number as a [[little endian]] unsigned 2 byte integer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.rs/nom/2.2.1/nom/fn.le_u16.html|title=nom::le_u16 - Rust|website=docs.rs|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> and <math>\nH\\_tcn()\n</math> is the SHA-256 hash function as <math>\nH\\_tcn(s) = SHA256(\\text{b'H}\\_\\text{TCN'}||s)[0:128]\n</math>. The following diagram demonstrates the key derivation process:[[File:TCN_Protocol_Key_Generation.svg|center]]TCNs are unique to each device encounter, and RAK-RVK pairs are cycled at regular intervals to allow a client to report only specific periods of contact. \n\n=== Reporting ===\nWhen a client wishes to submit a report for the TCN indicies <math>\ns > 0\n</math> to <math>\ne\n</math>, it structures the report as <math>\nreport = rvk || tck_{s - 1} || le\\_u16(s) || le\\_u16(e) || memo\n</math>. A signature is then calculated using the RAK, and it is transmitted to the server as <math>\ns\\_report = report||sig\n</math>.\n\nBecause any given TCK can only be used to derive an equal or higher indexed TCNs, by submitting <math>\ntck_{s-1}\n</math> no encounters prior to <math>\ntcn_{s-1}\n</math> can be calculated. However there is no upper limit to encounters calculated using the same RAK-RVK pair, which is why they are cycled often. To prevent clients calculating unused TCNs, <math>\ne\n</math> indicates the last TCN index generated with the given RVK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/TCNCoalition/tcn-client-android/blob/develop/tcn-client-android/src/main/java/org/tcncoalition/tcnclient/TcnKeys.kt|title=TCNCoalition/tcn-client-android/src/main/java/org/tcncoalition/tcnclient/TcnKeys.kt|last=|first=|date=|website=GitHub|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>{{Rp|lines. 49-61}} Additionally, since the RVK is used to calculate a TCK, and <math>\ntck_{s-1}\n</math> is provided, no valid TCNs in the reporting period can be derived from an illegitimate report. The only correct TCN calculable from a mismatched RVK and <math>\ntck_{s-1}\n</math> is <math>\ntcn_{s-1}\n</math>, the TCN before the start of the reporting period.\n\nOnce a report is received, clients individually recalculate TCKs and TCNs for a given period using the original algorithms:<math display=\"block\">\n\\begin{array}{lcr}\ntck_s = H\\_tck(rvk || tck_{s-1})\\\\\ntcn_{s} = H\\_tcn(le\\_u16(s) || tck_{s})\\\\\ntck_{s+1} = H\\_tck(rvk || tck_{s})\\\\\ntcn_{s+1} = H\\_tcn(le\\_u16(s+1) || tck_{s+1})\\\\\n...\\\\\ntck_{e} = H\\_tck(rvk || tck_{e-1})\\\\\ntcn_{e} = H\\_tcn(le\\_u16(e) || tck_{e})\n\\end{array}\n</math>This is used by client devices to check their local contact logs for potential encounters with the infected patient, but has the dual benefit of verifying reports since false reports will never produce matching TCNs.\n\n=== Memo ===\nIn the report structure, the memo is a space for freeform messages that differ between TCN implementations. The section is between 2 and 257 bytes, and made up of a tag identifying the specific implementation, as well as a data and data length pair. It is formatted as  <math>\nmemo = tag || len(data) || data\n</math>. The data is standardized for different tags, and can be as follows:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Tag\n!Data standard\n|-\n|{{Code|code=0x0}}\n|[[CoEpi]] symptom report v1\n|-\n|{{Code|code=0x1}}\n|[[CovidWatch]] test result v1\n|-\n|{{Code|code=0x2-0xfe}}\n|Allocated for future official TCN apps or versions\n|-\n|{{Code|code=0xff}}\n|Reserved (can be used to add more than 256 types later)\n|}\n\n== Technical specification ==\nThe protocol can be divided into two responsibilities: an encounter between two devices running TCN apps, and the notification of potential infection to users that came in contact with a patient. For the purposes of this specification, these areas are named the ''encounter handshake'', and ''infection reporting''. The ''encounter handshake'' runs on Bluetooth LE and defines how two devices acknowledge each other's presence. The ''infection reporting'' is built on [[Hypertext Transfer Protocol|HTTPS]] and defines how infection notices are distributed among clients.\n\n=== Encounter handshake ===\nWhen two devices come within range of each other, they exchange a handshake containing TCNs. In order to achieve this the encounter handshake operates in two modes (both with two sub-modes), broadcast oriented and connection oriented. Broadcast oriented operates using the modes broadcaster and observer, while connection oriented operates using peripheral and central. The two modes are used to circumvent certain device limitations, particularly in regard to iOS restrictions in place before version 13.4.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/iOSBeta/comments/fcww2x/feature_ios_134_beta_enables_ble_long_range/|title=r/iOSBeta - [Feature] IOS 13.4 beta enables BLE long range support (iPhone 11/11 Pro only)|website=reddit|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> In both modes the protocol is identified with the 16 bit [[Universally unique identifier|UUID]] {{Code|code=0xC019}}.\n\nIn broadcast mode, a broadcaster advertises a 16-byte TCN using the service data field of the advertisement data. The observer reads the TCN from this field. In connection-oriented mode, the peripheral advertises using the UUID. The service exposes a read and writeable packet for sharing TCNs. After sharing a TCN, the central disconnects from the peripheral.\n\n=== Infection reporting ===\nWhen a user tests positive for infection, they upload a signed report allowing the past 14 days of encounters to be calculated to a central server. On a regular basis, client devices download reports from the server and check their local contact logs using the verification algorithm. If there is a matching record, the app notifies the user to potential infection.\n\n== TCN Coalition ==\nOn 5 April 2020, the global [[TCN Coalition]] was founded by groups that had coalesced around what was essentially the same approach and largely overlapping protocols, with the goal to reduce fragmentation, and enable global interoperability of tracing and alerting apps, a key aspect of achieving widespread adoption.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://tcn-coalition.org/|title=TCN Coalition \u00b7 A Global Coalition for Privacy-First Digital Contact Tracing Protocols to Fight COVID-19|website=tcn-coalition.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The TCN Coalition also helped establish the [[Data Rights for Digital Contact Tracing and Alerting]] framework, which functions as a bill of rights for users of such apps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dcta-datarights.com/|title=Data Rights for Digital Contact Tracing and Alerting \u00b7 Overview|last=Reed <questions@dcta-datarights.org>|first=Harper|website=dcta-datarights.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nCurrently the protocol is currently used by TCN Coalition members [[CoEpi]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miragenews.com/will-smartphones-help-us-keep-covid-19-under-control/,%20https://www.miragenews.com/will-smartphones-help-us-keep-covid-19-under-control|title=Will Smartphones Help Us Keep COVID-19 Under Control? {{!}} Mirage News|last=News|first=Mirage|date=2020-04-15|website=www.miragenews.com|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Co-Epi/app-android|date=2020-04-19|url=https://github.com/Co-Epi/app-android|publisher=CoEpi|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> and [[CovidWatch]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.covid-watch.org/|title=Covid Watch|website=www.covid-watch.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> and was likely a source of inspiration for the similar [[Google / Apple contact tracing project]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://covid-watch.org/press_releases/google_apple_press_release|title=Covid Watch Celebrates Apple and Google\u2019s COVID-19 Contact Tracing Announcement|last=|first=|date=|website=www.covid-watch.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[BlueTrace]]\n* [[Google / Apple contact tracing project]]\n*[[Pan-European Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing]]\n\n== References ==\n\n<references />{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}{{FOSS}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://tcn-coalition.org/ TCN Coalition]\n* [https://github.com/TCNCoalition/TCN Specification and reference implementation]\n\n[[Category:Application layer protocols]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2020]]\n[[Category:Software associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Bluetooth software]]\n[[Category:Medical software]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:IOS software]]\n[[Category:2020 software]]\n[[Category:Software using the MIT license]]\n[[Category:Digital contact tracing protocols]]\n", "name_user": "Nyq", "label": "safe", "comment": "Decapitalized acronym expansion as perMOS:CAPSACRS, decapitalized common noun", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TCN_Protocol"}
{"title_page": "L\u0101\u2018au lapa\u2018au", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''L\u0101\u2018au lapa\u2018au''' is a traditional medical practice adopted by native [[Hawaiians]]. The Hawaiian words, L\u0101\u2018au translates to vegetation (plant, tree, timber, forest) and lapa\u2018au translates to treat, heal and [[cure]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kahunahaleolono.org/language.html|title=Authentic Hawaiian Kahuna Lomilomi and Laau Lapaau share their ancient wisdom in healing paractices.|website=www.kahunahaleolono.org|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> This practice involves using native plants, herbs and spirituality to treat ailments and injuries. Traditionally, L\u0101\u2018au lapa\u2018au is practiced by [[Native Hawaiians|Native Hawaiian]] healers known as [[Kahuna]] L\u0101\u2018au lapa\u2018au.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Kahuna_La_au_Lapa_au.html?id=-zsTAQAAIAAJ|title=Kahuna La'au Lapa'au: The Practice of Hawaiian Herbal Medicine|last=Gutmanis|first=June|date=1976|publisher=Island Heritage|isbn=9780896100787|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nThe history of L\u0101\u2018au lapa\u2018au has been shared by past generations for over a thousand years. In the Native Hawaiian culture, it is believed that health is a result of pono or right living and the belief that that that the loss of harmony and balance caused illness. Traditional Native Hawaiian medicinal practices were based on holistic healing in which the mind, body and spirit were all intertwined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://share.nned.net/2018/03/laau-lapaau-preserving-ancient-hawaiian-healing-practices/|title=La\u2019au Lapa\u2019au: Preserving Ancient Hawaiian Healing Practices|date=2018-03-06|website=NNEDShare|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n\n[[Kahuna]] l\u0101\u02bbau lapa\u02bbau<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/kahuna+lapaau|title=Definition of KAHUNA LAPAAU|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> were known as the experts in l\u0101\u02bbau lapa\u02bbau and are comparable to [[general practitioner]]s of today. In order to become a Kahuna&nbsp;l\u0101\u02bbau lapa\u02bbau, one had to study for many decades and practice understanding the different healing properties of the la\u02bbau. Kahuna l\u0101\u02bbau lapa\u02bbau is responsible for gathering, preparing and administering herbs based off of two things, the needs of the patient and the healing properties of the herbs / la\u02bbau .<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lapaau.org/about/|title=About|website=Lapaau.org|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n\nExamples of the most common la\u02bbau used for healing include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://keolamagazine.com/agriculture/medicinal-plants/|title=La\u2018au Lapa\u2018au: Medicinal Plants and their Healing Properties|last=Magazine|first=Ke Ola|date=2018-09-01|website=Ke Ola Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Known Healing La\u02bbau\n!Hawaiian Name\n!Scientific Name\n!Healing Purpose\n|-\n|\u2018Awa (Kava)\n|''[[Kava|Piper methysticum]]''\n|Used to treat tiredness, chills, latent childhood disease, kidney disorders, headaches, and insomnia.\n|-\n|\u2018Awapuhi Kuahiwi\n|''[[Zingiber zerumbet]]''\n|Used to treat toothache, sprains, stomachache, achy joints,  ringworm, and other skin diseases.\n|-\n|Noni\n|''[[Morinda citrifolia]]''\n|Used to treat kidney stones, high blood pressure, diabetes, and bowel problems.\n|}\nThere are many parallels to L\u0101\u2018au lapa\u2018au in other [[Polynesian culture]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/nativevoices/exhibition/healing-ways/medicine-ways/healing-plants.html|title=Healing Plants - Medicine Ways: Traditional Healers and Healing - Healing Ways - Exhibition - Native Voices|website=www.nlm.nih.gov|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Traditional healthcare occupations]]\n[[Category:Supernatural healing]]\n[[Category:Hawaii]]\n", "text_old": "'''L\u0101\u2018au lapa\u2018au''' is a traditional medical practice adopted by native [[Hawaiians]]. The Hawaiian words, L\u0101\u2018au translates to vegetation (plant, tree, timber, forest) and lapa\u2018au translates to treat, heal and [[cure]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kahunahaleolono.org/language.html|title=Authentic Hawaiian Kahuna Lomilomi and Laau Lapaau share their ancient wisdom in healing paractices.|website=www.kahunahaleolono.org|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> This practice involves using native plants, herbs and spirituality to treat ailments and injuries. Traditionally, L\u0101\u2018au lapa\u2018au is practiced by [[Native Hawaiians|Native Hawaiian]] healers known as [[Kahuna]] L\u0101\u2018au lapa\u2018au. <ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Kahuna_La_au_Lapa_au.html?id=-zsTAQAAIAAJ|title=Kahuna La'au Lapa'au: The Practice of Hawaiian Herbal Medicine|last=Gutmanis|first=June|date=1976|publisher=Island Heritage|isbn=9780896100787|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nThe history of L\u0101\u2018au lapa\u2018au has been shared by past generations for over a thousand years. In the Native Hawaiian culture, it is believed that health is a result of pono or right living and the belief that that that the loss of harmony and balance caused illness. Traditional Native Hawaiian medicinal practices were based on holistic healing in which the mind, body and spirit were all intertwined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://share.nned.net/2018/03/laau-lapaau-preserving-ancient-hawaiian-healing-practices/|title=La\u2019au Lapa\u2019au: Preserving Ancient Hawaiian Healing Practices|date=2018-03-06|website=NNEDShare|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n\n[[Kahuna]] l\u0101\u02bbau lapa\u02bbau<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/kahuna+lapaau|title=Definition of KAHUNA LAPAAU|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> were known as the experts in l\u0101\u02bbau lapa\u02bbau and are comparable to [[General practitioner|general practitioners]] of today. In order to become a Kahuna&nbsp;l\u0101\u02bbau lapa\u02bbau, one had to study for many decades and practice understanding the different healing properties of the la\u02bbau. Kahuna l\u0101\u02bbau lapa\u02bbau is responsible for gathering, preparing and administering herbs based off of two things, the needs of the patient and the healing properties of the herbs / la\u02bbau .<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lapaau.org/about/|title=About|website=Lapaau.org|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n\nExamples of the most common la\u02bbau used for healing include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://keolamagazine.com/agriculture/medicinal-plants/|title=La\u2018au Lapa\u2018au: Medicinal Plants and their Healing Properties|last=Magazine|first=Ke Ola|date=2018-09-01|website=Ke Ola Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Known Healing La\u02bbau\n!Hawaiian Name\n!Scientific Name\n!Healing Purpose\n|-\n|\u2018Awa (Kava)\n|''[[Kava|Piper methysticum]]''\n|Used to treat tiredness, chills, latent childhood disease, kidney disorders, headaches, and insomnia.\n|-\n|\u2018Awapuhi Kuahiwi\n|''[[Zingiber zerumbet]]''\n|Used to treat toothache, sprains, stomachache, achy joints,  ringworm, and other skin diseases.\n|-\n|Noni\n|''[[Morinda citrifolia]]''\n|Used to treat kidney stones, high blood pressure, diabetes, and bowel problems.\n|}\nThere are many parallels to L\u0101\u2018au lapa\u2018au in other [[Polynesian culture|Polynesian cultures]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/nativevoices/exhibition/healing-ways/medicine-ways/healing-plants.html|title=Healing Plants - Medicine Ways: Traditional Healers and Healing - Healing Ways - Exhibition - Native Voices|website=www.nlm.nih.gov|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Traditional healthcare occupations]]\n[[Category:Supernatural healing]]\n[[Category:Hawaii]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addedorphantag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L%C4%81%E2%80%98au_lapa%E2%80%98au"}
{"title_page": "Animal Crossing", "text_new": "{{short description|Video game series developed by Nintendo}}\n{{about|the video game series|the first game in the series|Animal Crossing (video game)|other uses|}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game series\n| width = 400\n| title = Animal Crossing\n| image = Animal_Crossing_Logo.png\n| caption = ''Animal Crossing'' series logo\n| genre = [[Social simulation game|Social simulation]]\n| creator = [[Katsuya Eguchi]]\n| developer = {{Unbulleted list|[[Nintendo EAD]]|[[Nintendo Entertainment Planning & Development|Nintendo EPD]]|[[NDcube]]}}\n| publisher = [[Nintendo]]\n| platforms = {{Hlist|[[Nintendo 64]]|[[iQue Player]]|[[GameCube]]|[[Wii]]|[[Wii U]]|[[Nintendo DS]]|[[Nintendo 3DS]]|[[iOS]]|[[Android (operating system)|Android]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]}}\n| first release version = ''[[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]''\n| first release date = April 14, 2001\n| latest release version = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]]''\n| latest release date = March 20, 2020\n| spinoffs = {{Unbulleted list|''[[Happy Home Designer]]''|''[[Amiibo Festival]]''|''[[Pocket Camp]]''}}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Animal Crossing'''''|\u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee|D\u014dbutsu no Mori|''Animal Forest''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[social simulation game|social simulation]] [[video game]] series developed and published by [[Nintendo]] and created by [[Katsuya Eguchi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.droidgamers.com/2014/03/27/while-animal-crossing-may-never-see-a-mobile-game-there-could-be-companion-apps-on-the-way/|title=While Animal Crossing may never see a mobile game, there could be companion apps on the way|author=Andrew H|website=droidgamers.com|date=March 27, 2014|accessdate=February 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304072130/http://www.droidgamers.com/index.php/apps/7395-while-animal-crossing-may-never-see-a-mobile-game-there-could-be-companion-apps-on-the-way|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/no-retro-games-in-future-animal-crossings-with-one-poss-512085493|title=No Retro Games in Future Animal Crossings\u2014With One Possible Exception|author=Stephen Totilo|website=kotaku.com|date=June 8, 2013|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/e3-08-nintendo-press-conference/|title=E3 08: Nintendo Press Conference|author=Brett Elston|website=gamesradar.com|date=July 15, 2008|accessdate=February 24, 2016}}</ref> In ''Animal Crossing'', the [[player character]] is a human who lives in a village inhabited by various [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] animals, carrying out various activities such as fishing, bug catching, and fossil hunting. The series is notable for its [[Nonlinear gameplay|open-ended]] gameplay and extensive use of the [[video game console]]'s internal clock and calendar to simulate [[Real time (media)|real passage of time]].\n\nSince its [[Animal Crossing (video game)|initial release]] in 2001, five ''Animal Crossing'' games have been released worldwide, one each for the [[Nintendo 64]]/[[iQue Player]] (enhanced and reissued for the [[GameCube]]), [[Nintendo DS]], [[Wii]], [[Nintendo 3DS]] and [[Nintendo Switch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/news/animal-crossing-on-nintendo-switch|title=Animal Crossing on Nintendo Switch: release date, news and features|last=Hood|first=Vic|last2=Gaming|first2=Nick Pino 2019-06-18T17:06:19Z|website=TechRadar|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> The series has been both critically and commercially successful and has sold over 30 million units worldwide. Three spin-off games have also been released: ''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer]]'' for [[Nintendo 3DS]], ''[[Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival]]'' for [[Wii U]], and ''[[Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp]]'' for mobile devices.\n\n== Common elements ==\n\n=== Characters ===\n{{main|Characters in the Animal Crossing series}}\nWhile the series features various villagers for each title, certain prominent characters return in each series installment. [[Tom Nook]] is a [[Japanese raccoon dog|tanuki]] character who functions as both a shop owner and real estate broker, giving the player a loan for their house and allowing them to pay it back with no interest. He is one of the only residents of the town to follow a [[Capitalism|capitalist]] ethos. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/tom-nook-needs-to-get-with-the-times-1829149177|title=Tom Nook Needs To Get With The Times|last=Jackson|first=Gita|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> [[Mr. Resetti]] is a mole character who appears from underground whenever players shut off the game without saving, berating them for circumventing one of the game's systems. Due to a new [[autosave]] function, he was \"laid off\" from his job in ''Animal Crossing: New Horizons'', although he has gotten a new job as the Rescue Service operator. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2019/06/17/animal-crossing-new-horizons-autosave-resettis-job/|title=Animal Crossing New Horizons has autosave, so Resetti's out of a job|date=2019-06-17|website=VG247|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n[[K.K. Slider]] is a canine traveling musician based on series composer [[Kazumi Totaka]], and plays on certain nights in the town's club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/05/profile_kazumi_totaka_the_man_behind_animal_crossings_kk_slider|title=Profile: Kazumi Totaka - The Man Behind Animal Crossing's K.K. Slider|last=Life|first=Nintendo|date=2013-05-08|website=Nintendo Life|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> Afterwards, he gifts the player a free copy of the song played, saying that his music \"wants to be free\". This was seen by some fans as tacit support for [[music piracy]], although Nintendo denied that it was intended as [[social commentary]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/19/technology/social-commentary-or-just-a-dogs-opinion.html|title=Social Commentary, or Just a Dog's Opinion?|last=Jr|first=Tom Zeller|date=2005-12-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Gameplay===\nIn the ''Animal Crossing'' games, the player assumes the role of a  child, aged between any age, who moves into a rural village populated with anthropomorphic animals and lives there indefinitely. Gameplay is [[Nonlinear gameplay|open-ended]]: players have no defined objectives, but are instead encouraged to spend their time in the village performing any number of activities, which include collecting items, planting plants or other items, and socializing with the village's residents. ''Animal Crossing'' games are played in [[Real time (media)|real time]], utilizing the [[video game console]]'s internal clock and calendar. Thus, passage of time in the game world reflects that in reality, as well as the current season and time of day. Some in-game events, such as holidays or the growth of a tree, occur at certain times or require some duration of time to have passed.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_preview\"/>\n\nOne notable feature of the ''Animal Crossing'' series is the high level of customization available, some of which affects the outcome of the game.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\" /> The [[player character]] is both named and gendered by the real life player at the start of the game, and their appearance can be modified by buying or designing custom clothes and accessories or changing the hairstyle (introduced in ''[[Animal Crossing: Wild World|Wild World]]''). The player's house can also be furnished, decorated, and later expanded: the player can purchase and collect furniture and place it anywhere in the house, as well as change both the wallpaper and floor designs. While its terrain, building locations, and initial residents are randomly generated when the game is first begun (except in ''Animal Crossing: New Leaf'', in which the player decides between four given towns, and ''Animal Crossing: New Horizons'', in which the player similarly decides between four given islands), the village's name and anthem, as well as some of the residents' catchphrases, are also determined by the player.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\"/>\n\nCollecting items is a major facet of ''Animal Crossing'': the player can explore the village and gather objects, including fruit from trees, seashells, and discarded items. Nearly all objects can be sold for Bells, the in-game currency. Players collect objects to obtain more Bells, which can then be used to buy furniture and clothing, purchase home expansions, invest in stocks, and play games. A number of specialized tools are available for other activities such as fishing and insect collecting. Special items, such as fossils and paintings, may be donated to the village museum. The player can choose to socialize with the other animal residents by engaging in conversation, sending and receiving letters, bartering, or playing hide-and-seek. Residents may move in or out of the village depending on the player's actions.\n\nAll installments of ''Animal Crossing'' allow some form of communication between players, both offline and [[Online game|online]]. A single village can house up to four human players, though only one can be exploring the village at any given time.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_preview\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing Preview |last=Schneider |first=Peer |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/05/30/animal-crossing |date=May 30, 2002 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The players can interact via written messages through the village post office or bulletin board. The [[GameCube]] iteration allowed players to travel to other villages by trading [[Nintendo GameCube#Memory and storage|memory cards]] written with the game data,<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\"/> but all subsequent installments allow players to travel and interact online via [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection]], although ''[[Animal Crossing: City Folk|City Folk]]'' also allows the DS Suitcase to travel to others' towns.<ref name=\"IGN_DS_review\"/><ref name=\"IGN_Wii_review\"/>\n\n==Games==\n\n{{Timeline of release years\n| summary = Timeline of releases in the ''Animal Crossing'' series, from 2001 to present.\n| range1       = 2001 \u2013\n| range1_color = #ffc836 #e5d2ac <!-- Based on series logo -->\n| 2001 = ''[[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]''\n| 2005 = ''[[Animal Crossing: Wild World|Wild World]]''\n| 2008 = ''[[Animal Crossing: City Folk|City Folk]]''\n| 2012 = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf|New Leaf]]''\n| 2015a = ''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer|Happy Home Designer]]''\n| 2015b = ''[[Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival|Amiibo Festival]]''\n| 2016 = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf|New Leaf \u2013 Welcome Amiibo]]''\n| 2017 = ''[[Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp|Pocket Camp]]''\n| 2020 = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Horizons|New Horizons]]''\n}}\n\n===Main series===\n\n====''Animal Crossing'' (2001)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing (video game)}}\n''Animal Crossing''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Animal Forest''}}}} was originally released in Japan for the [[Nintendo 64]] on April 14, 2001. It was enhanced and released on the [[GameCube]] the same year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/13/the-evolution-of-animal-crossing-2?page=2 |title=The Evolution of Animal Crossing (page 2) |last=Harris |first=Craig |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> This version was localized and released in North America on September 16, 2002, Australia on October 17, 2003, and Europe on September 24, 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/action-replay-ultimate-codes-animal-crossing/gcn-16562 |title=Animal Crossing Review |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> An extended version titled \"D\u014dbutsu no Mori e+\" was released on June 27, 2003 in Japan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/doubutsu-no-mori/gcn-552545 |title=Doubutsu no Mori e+ |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The Nintendo 64 version of the game was released in China in 2006 for [[iQue Player]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ique.com/games/21041.htm |title=Animal Forest |publisher=iQue Ltd. |language=Chinese |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Wild World'' (2005)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Wild World}}\n''Animal Crossing: Wild World''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Oideyo D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u304a\u3044\u3067\u3088 \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Come to Animal Forest''}}}} was released for the [[Nintendo DS]] in Japan on November 23, 2005, North America on December 5, 2005, Australia on December 8, 2005, and Europe on March 31, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/animal-crossing-wild-world/nds-682878 |title=Animal Crossing: Wild World Review |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was the first game in the series to use [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection]]. The game was later re-released on the [[Wii U]] [[Virtual Console]] on October 13, 2016, although its Wi-Fi multiplayer feature is unavailable due to the [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection#Closing|discontinuation]] of Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection.\n\n====''Animal Crossing: City Folk'' (2008)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: City Folk}}\n''Animal Crossing: City Folk'',{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Machi e Ik\u014d yo D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u8857\u3078\u884c\u3053\u3046\u3088 \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Let's Go to the City: Animal Forest''}}}} known as ''Animal Crossing: Let's Go to the City'' in Europe and Australia, was released for the [[Wii]] in North America on November 16, 2008, Japan on November 20, 2008, Australia on December 4, 2008, and Europe on December 5, 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/animal-crossing-city-folk/wii-748892 |title=Animal Crossing: City Folk Review |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was later released in South Korea in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendo.co.kr/Wii/software/animal_crossing/main.php |title=\ud0c0\uc6b4\uc73c\ub85c \ub180\ub7ec\uac00\uc694 \ub3d9\ubb3c\uc758 \uc232 |publisher=Nintendo |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |language=Korean}}</ref> It was the first Wii game to utilize the [[Wii Speak]], an accessory that allows players to talk to each other during online play.\n\n====''Animal Crossing: New Leaf'' (2012)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: New Leaf}}\n''Animal Crossing: New Leaf''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Tobidase D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u3068\u3073\u3060\u305b \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Jump Out Animal Forest''}}}} was announced at [[E3 2010]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/06/15/e3-2010-animal-crossing-3ds-announced|title=E3 2010: Animal Crossing 3DS Announced|publisher=IGN|last=Thomas|first=Lucas M.|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was released for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] in Japan on November 8, 2012, North America on June 9, 2013, Europe on June 14, 2013, and Australia on June 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/animal-crossing-3ds/3ds-77803 |title=Animal Crossing: New Leaf |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> For the first time in the series, players are appointed to the role of Mayor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/10/25/animal-crossing-3ds-has-a-new-name|title=Animal Crossing 3DS Has a New Name|last=Drake|first=Audrey|publisher=IGN|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\nIn November 2016, a new update was released along with \"Welcome Amiibo\" in North America and Europe, adding several new locations, items and activities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome Amiibo|url=http://www.mojenintendo.cz/animal-crossing-new-leaf-welcome-amiibocard/|website=mojenintendo.cz|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====''Animal Crossing: New Horizons'' (2020)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: New Horizons}}\nA game in the series for [[Nintendo Switch]] was announced in a [[Nintendo Direct]] in September 2018, later revealed as ''Animal Crossing: New Horizons''.{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Atsumare D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u3042\u3064\u307e\u308c \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Gathering Animal Forest''}}}} Set on a deserted island, it was released on March 20, 2020 after initially being planned for release in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Plante |first1=Chris |title=Animal Crossing: New Horizons looks magical, but is delayed to March 2020 |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2019/6/11/18661310/nintendo-direct-e3-2019-animal-crossing-new-horizons-trailer-release-date |website=Polygon |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Spin-off games===\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer'' (2015)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer}}\n''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer]]'' is a [[Social simulation game|community simulation]] video game for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] and the first spin-off of the ''Animal Crossing'' series. It was released in Japan on July 30, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2015/05/animal-crossing-happy-home-designer-japanese-release-date-set|title=Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer Japanese release date set|last=Romano|first=Sal|publisher=Gematsu|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> North America on September 25, 2015,<ref name=\"meta-hhd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/animal-crossing-happy-home-designer|title=Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> Europe on October 2, 2015,<ref name=\"nwd-hhd\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/40828/animal-crossing-happy-home-designer-bundles-announced-for-uk-and-australia |title=Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer Bundles Announced for UK and Australia |publisher=Nintendo World Report |last=Abou-Nasr |first=Adam |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> and Australia on October 3, 2015.<ref name=\"nwd-hhd\" /> The game revolves around designing houses for villagers based on their requests. By scanning [[Amiibo]] cards, players can unlock the ability to design special characters' houses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/06/animal_crossing_director_talks_more_about_happy_home_designer_and_amiibo|title=Animal Crossing Director Talks More About Happy Home Designer and amiibo|publisher=Nintendo Life|last=Vogel|first=Mitch|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The game has a score of 66 out of 100 on [[Metacritic]], which signifies \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref name=\"meta-hhd\" />\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival'' (2015)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival}}\n''[[Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival]]'' is a [[Party video game|party]] video game for the [[Wii U]] released in November 2015 that heavily utilizes [[Amiibo]]. It was met with unfavorable reviews from critics.<ref name=\"meta-af\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/animal-crossing-amiibo-festival/critic-reviews |title=Animal Crossing: amiibo Festival |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was developed by [[Nintendo Entertainment Planning & Development]] and [[NDcube]].\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp'' (2017)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp}}\nIn April 2016, Nintendo announced that an ''Animal Crossing'' mobile game, later named as ''[[Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp]]'', would be released as a part of their [[Nintendo mobile games|mobile game lineup]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Seedhouse|first1=Alex|title=Next Nintendo Apps Will Use Fire Emblem & Animal Crossing Franchises|url=http://www.nintendo-insider.com/2016/04/next-nintendo-apps-will-use-fire-emblem-animal-crossing-franchises/|website=Nintendo Insider|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The game was soft launched in Australia in October 2017, and released worldwide on November 21, 2017.\n\n===Apps===\n* ''[[Animal Crossing Plaza]]'', a [[Wii U system software#WaraWara Plaza|WaraWara Plaza]]-like app for [[Wii U]]. Limited time promotion for ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]''.\n* ''Animal Crossing Clock'', a Clock system app for [[Nintendo DSi]] and [[Nintendo 3DS]].\n* ''Animal Crossing Calculator'', a Calculator app for [[Nintendo DSi]] and [[Nintendo 3DS]].\n* ''Photos with Animal Crossing'', a Camera app for [[Nintendo 3DS]] allowing players to take photos with Animal Crossing characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nintendoeverything.com/photos-with-animal-crossing-nintendo-uk-summer-tour-2015-video/#disqus_thread|title=Photos with Animal Crossing - Nintendo UK Summer Tour 2015 video|work=Nintendo Everything|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\n{{Video game series reviews\n|updated = March 18, 2020\n|sales_title = Units sold<br />{{small|(in millions)}}\n\n|game1 = [[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]\n|year1 = 2001\n|sales1 = 2.32<ref name=\"GC_NA_sales\"/><ref name=\"GC_JP_sales\"/>\n|mc1 = 87/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/gamecube/animal-crossing |title=''Animal Crossing'' (GCN) at Metacritic |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |publisher=Metacritic.com}}</ref>\n\n|game2 = [[Animal Crossing: Wild World]]\n|year2 = 2005\n|sales2 = 11.75<ref name=\"DS_sales\"/>\n|mc2 = 86/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ds/animal-crossing-wild-world |title=Animal Crossing: Wild World |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|game3 = [[Animal Crossing: City Folk]]\n|year3 = 2008\n|sales3 = 3.38<ref name=\"Wii_sales\"/>\n|mc3 = 73/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii/animal-crossing-city-folk|title=''Animal Crossing: City Folk'' reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|game4 = [[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]\n|year4 = 2012\n|sales4 = 12.21<ref name =\"3DS-top-sell\"/>\n|mc4 = 88/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/animal-crossing-new-leaf |title=Animal Crossing: New Leaf |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|game5 = [[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]]\n|year5 = 2020\n|sales5 = 3.03 <ref> {{ cite web |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2020/04/japanese_charts_animal_crossing_new_horizons_surpasses_mario_kart_8_deluxe_lifetime_physical_sales |title=Japanese Charts: Animal Crossing: New Horizons Surpasses Mario Kart 8 Deluxe Lifetime Physical Sales |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|mc5 = 91/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/animal-crossing-new-horizons|title=Animal Crossing: New Horizons |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe ''Animal Crossing'' games have garnered positive response.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing Review |last=Schneider |first=Peer |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/09/05/animal-crossing-review |date=September 5, 2002 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN_DS_review\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing: Wild World Review |last=Harris |first=Craig |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/12/06/animal-crossing-wild-world |date=December 5, 2005 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN_Wii_review\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing: City Folk Review |last=Harris |first=Craig |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/17/animal-crossing-city-folk-review |date=November 16, 2008 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The first four main series games are among the [[List of best-selling video games|best-selling video games]] for their respective consoles. ''Animal Crossing'' has sold 2.32 million copies;<ref name=\"GC_NA_sales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-USPlatinum.shtml|title=US Platinum Videogame Chart|publisher=The Magic Box|accessdate=February 13, 2017|date= December 27, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"GC_JP_sales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-gamecharts.com/gc.php|title= Nintendo Gamecube Japanese Ranking|publisher= Japan Game Charts|date=May 6, 2007|accessdate=February 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070723025415/http://www.japan-gamecharts.com/gc.php|archive-date=July 23, 2007}}</ref> ''Wild World'' 11.75 million;<ref name=\"DS_sales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/sales/software/ds.html|title=Financial  Results Briefing for Fiscal Year Ended March 2014|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|date=December 6, 2014| format=PDF|accessdate=February 13, 2017|pages=6}}</ref> ''City Folk'' 3.38 million;<ref name=\"Wii_sales\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2009/090508e.pdf#page=6|title=Financial Results Briefing for the Fiscal Year Ended March 2009: Supplementary Information|accessdate=February 13, 2017|date=May 8, 2009|work=Financial Results Briefing for the 69th Fiscal Term Ended March 2009|publisher=Nintendo|pages=6}}</ref> ''New Leaf'' 12.21 million,<ref name =\"3DS-top-sell\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/sales/software/3ds.html|title=IR Information : Sales Data - Top Selling Software Sales Units - Nintendo 3DS Software|website=Nintendo|accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref> and ''Happy Home Designer'' 3.04 million.<ref name=\"HHD sales\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2016/160427_4e.pdf |title=Supplementary Information about Earnings Release |date=April 27, 2016 |publisher=Nintendo |page=4 |format=PDF |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> ''Amiibo Festival'' was a critical and commercial failure; in Japan it has only sold 26,325 copies.<ref name=\"meta-af\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/117/G011794/20151202067/ |title=\u300c\u30e2\u30f3\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30cf\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30af\u30ed\u30b9\u300d\u72e9\u731f\u89e3\u7981\u3067\u521d\u9031\u8ca9\u58f2\u6570148\u4e07\u672c\u306e\u300c\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u9031\u9593\u8ca9\u58f2\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\uff0b\u300d |work=[[4Gamer.net]] |publisher=Aetas Inc. |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |language=Japanese}}</ref> In total, the ''Animal Crossing'' franchise has sold over 30 million units.\n\n===Female demographic===\nFormer president of [[Nintendo]], [[Satoru Iwata]] noted that 56% of people who pre-ordered ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]'' identified as female, with many of them purchasing a [[Nintendo 3DS]] specifically for the game. He found the game's success with adult women between the ages of 19 to 24 to be particularly noteworthy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2013/02/10/a-lot-of-women-bought-a-3ds-for-animal-crossing-new-leaf-in-japan/ |title=A Lot Of Women Bought A 3DS For Animal Crossing: New Leaf In Japan |website=Siliconera |date=February 10, 2013 |access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2013/01/08/satoru-iwata-on-animal-crossing-sales-56-of-players-are-female/ |title=Satoru Iwata On Animal Crossing Sales, 56% Of Players Are Female |website=Siliconera |date=January 8, 2013 |access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://mashable.com/2014/04/02/animal-crossing-gender-gaming/ |title=More Women Game Developers Means More Success, 'Animal Crossing' Director Says |website=Mashable |date=April 2, 2014 |access-date=September 17, 2018 |first=Chelsea |last=Stark}}</ref>\n\n===Hong Kong protests===\nDuring the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]], ''[[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]]'' was used by democracy activists in Hong Kong as a platform to protest. In reaction, the game, although not officially available in China, has been officially removed from online stores such as Taobao, but parallel import copies continue to remain on sale.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nintendo-china-animalcrossing/nintendo-game-pulled-from-chinese-platforms-after-hong-kong-protest-idUSKCN21S11F |title=Nintendo game pulled from Chinese platforms after Hong Kong protest |website=Reuters|date=April 10, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n[[File:Villager (character).png|thumb|The male Villager, as depicted in ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'']]\nAn [[anime]] [[film adaptation]] of ''Wild World'', titled ''[[D\u014dbutsu no Mori (film)|D\u014dbutsu no Mori]]'', was released in Japan on December 16, 2006. The film was produced by [[OLM, Inc.]] and distributed by [[Toho]]. ''D\u014dbutsu no Mori'' earned [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]]1.8 billion (approximately $19.2 million) in the [[box office]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.rakuten.co.jp/movie/ranking/boxoffice/2007/ |title=2007\u5e74\u5ea6\u8208\u884c\u6210\u7e3e\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 |language=Japanese |publisher=Rakuten |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121029165113/http://entertainment.rakuten.co.jp/movie/ranking/boxoffice/2007/ |archivedate=October 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the Wii game ''[[WarioWare: Smooth Moves]]'', released in Japan in 2006 and Europe, North America and Australia in 2007, there is a minigame that is modeled after Animal Crossing: Wild World, [[mariowiki:Animal Crossing: Wild World|under the same name]]. The player has to catch a fish using the same mechanics as the original game.\n\nThe 2008 Wii game ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]'' features elements from ''Wild World''. Most prominent is a stage based on the animal village, called \"Smashville\", which changes its scenery in accordance with the Wii system clock<ref name=\"smash_stage\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Smashville |date=July 13, 2007 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/stages/stage06.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> and features a number of [[Video game music|songs]] remixed or extracted from the original game.<ref name=\"smash_music\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Full Song List with Secret Songs |date=April 3, 2008 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/music/music24_list.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> Mr. Resetti and a pitfall seed, which appear in all ''Animal Crossing'' games, are available as an Assist Trophy and an item respectively.<ref name=\"smash_resetti\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Mr. Resetti |date=September 26, 2007 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/items/assist/assist08.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"smash_pitfall\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Pitfall |date=September 26, 2007 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/items/item06.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> ''Brawl'' also features 24 collectible trophies based on ''Animal Crossing'' characters and items.<ref name=\"smash_trophies\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Trophy List |date=April 8, 2008 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/various/various36_list.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[Wii Music]]'' features two playable songs from ''Animal Crossing''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.destructoid.com/here-s-the-rest-of-the-wii-music-tracklist-108429.phtml |title=Here's the rest of the Wii Music tracklist |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=North |first=Dale |date=October 20, 2008 |work=[[Destructoid]]}}</ref>\n\nThe minigame \"Animal Crossing: Sweet Day\" in ''[[Nintendo Land]]'' is based on the ''Animal Crossing'' game series. The objective of the game is for the Wii Remote players (1-4), to gather large amounts of candy scattered around the area and store them in their head without getting caught by the Gatekeepers, who are controlled using the two Wii U GamePad analog sticks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/uk/products/nintendo-land-wii-u/review/2/ |title=Nintendo Land (Wii U) review |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=Petit |first=Carolyn |date=November 18, 2012 |work=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>\n\nA playable character called \"Villager\" represents the ''Animal Crossing'' series as a fighter in ''[[Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U]]'' and ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]''. The character has both male and female forms, which are selected when choosing the character. His or her moves include the ability to catch other players in a net and firing Lloid the gyroid as a missile.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2468841,00.asp |title=How to Beast With Villager, Mega Man in Super Smash Bros. 3DS Demo |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=Torres |first=Timothy |date=September 13, 2014 |work=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]}}</ref> Additionally, [[Isabelle (Animal Crossing)|Isabelle]] from ''New Leaf'' appears as an Assist Trophy,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wiiu-3ds/us/howto/entry6.html |title=Assist Trophies |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |work=[[Nintendo]]}}</ref> and later appeared as a standalone fighter in ''Ultimate''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/2018/09/13/super-smash-bros-ultimate-isabelle-animal-crossing/|title='Animal Crossing' Favorite Isabelle Joins 'Super Smash Bros. Ultimate' Roster|website=Comicbook.com}}</ref> Two new ''Animal Crossing'' stages appear in the games: \"Town & City\" from ''City Folk'' in the Wii U version, and \"Tortimer Island\" from ''New Leaf'' in the 3DS version.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wiiu-3ds/us/howto/entry4.html |title=Stages 1 |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |work=[[Nintendo]]}}</ref> \"Smashville\" from ''Brawl'' returns in the Wii U version.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/super-smash-bros-4-unlock-guide-characters-stages-how-wii-u-3ds-connect-10-million-us-sales-614833 |title=Super Smash Bros 4: Unlock Guide -- Characters and Stages; How Wii U and 3DS Connect; 10 Million US Sales |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=Bhat |first=Aditya |date=October 22, 2014 |work=[[International Business Times]] |publisher=[[IBT Media]]}}</ref>\n\nVillager and Isabelle are playable characters in ''[[Mario Kart 8]]'' via downloadable content, along with a racetrack based on ''Animal Crossing'' and a cup named after the series known as the \"Crossing Cup\".<ref name=\"Franchises coming to MK8\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/zelda-f-zero-coming-to-mario-kart-8-1627150730|title=Zelda, Animal Crossing Coming to Mario Kart 8 |publisher=Kotaku | first=Luke | last=Plunkett |date=August 26, 2014 |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The two racers, along with the ''Animal Crossing'' track, were also included in the [[Nintendo Switch]] version of the game, ''[[Mario Kart 8 Deluxe]]'' along with a racing suit based on the series for the [[Mii]]. In June 2015, Isabelle and Mr. Resetti-themed cosmetics were added as costumes options for the player's \"Palico\" companion in ''[[Monster Hunter 4 Ultimate]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/06/monster_hunter_4_ultimate_june_dlc_brings_animal_crossing_devil_may_cry_and_awesome_designs|title=Monster Hunter 4 Ultimate June DLC Brings Animal Crossing, Devil May Cry and Awesome Designs|work=Nintendo Life|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Video games|Japan}}\n*[[List of Animal Crossing media|List of ''Animal Crossing'' media]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.animal-crossing.com/}}\n\n{{Animal Crossing series}}\n{{Nintendo franchises}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Animal Crossing| ]]\n[[Category:Life simulation games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo franchises]]\n[[Category:Social simulation video games]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 2001]]\n[[Category:Video games about animals]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Video game series developed by Nintendo}}\n{{about|the video game series|the first game in the series|Animal Crossing (video game)|other uses|}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game series\n| width = 400\n| title = Animal Crossing\n| image = Animal_Crossing_Logo.png\n| caption = ''Animal Crossing'' series logo\n| genre = [[Social simulation game|Social simulation]]\n| creator = [[Katsuya Eguchi]]\n| developer = {{Unbulleted list|[[Nintendo EAD]]|[[Nintendo Entertainment Planning & Development|Nintendo EPD]]|[[NDcube]]}}\n| publisher = [[Nintendo]]\n| platforms = {{Hlist|[[Nintendo 64]]|[[iQue Player]]|[[GameCube]]|[[Wii]]|[[Wii U]]|[[Nintendo DS]]|[[Nintendo 3DS]]|[[iOS]]|[[Android (operating system)|Android]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]}}\n| first release version = ''[[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]''\n| first release date = April 14, 2001\n| latest release version = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]]''\n| latest release date = March 20, 2020\n| spinoffs = {{Unbulleted list|''[[Happy Home Designer]]''|''[[Amiibo Festival]]''|''[[Pocket Camp]]''}}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Animal Crossing'''''|\u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee|D\u014dbutsu no Mori|''Animal Forest''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[social simulation game|social simulation]] [[video game]] series developed and published by [[Nintendo]] and created by [[Katsuya Eguchi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.droidgamers.com/2014/03/27/while-animal-crossing-may-never-see-a-mobile-game-there-could-be-companion-apps-on-the-way/|title=While Animal Crossing may never see a mobile game, there could be companion apps on the way|author=Andrew H|website=droidgamers.com|date=March 27, 2014|accessdate=February 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304072130/http://www.droidgamers.com/index.php/apps/7395-while-animal-crossing-may-never-see-a-mobile-game-there-could-be-companion-apps-on-the-way|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/no-retro-games-in-future-animal-crossings-with-one-poss-512085493|title=No Retro Games in Future Animal Crossings\u2014With One Possible Exception|author=Stephen Totilo|website=kotaku.com|date=June 8, 2013|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/e3-08-nintendo-press-conference/|title=E3 08: Nintendo Press Conference|author=Brett Elston|website=gamesradar.com|date=July 15, 2008|accessdate=February 24, 2016}}</ref> In ''Animal Crossing'', the [[player character]] is a human who lives in a village inhabited by various [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] animals, carrying out various activities such as fishing, bug catching, and fossil hunting. The series is notable for its [[Nonlinear gameplay|open-ended]] gameplay and extensive use of the [[video game console]]'s internal clock and calendar to simulate [[Real time (media)|real passage of time]].\n\nSince its [[Animal Crossing (video game)|initial release]] in 2001, five ''Animal Crossing'' games have been released worldwide, one each for the [[Nintendo 64]]/[[iQue Player]] (enhanced and reissued for the [[GameCube]]), [[Nintendo DS]], [[Wii]], [[Nintendo 3DS]] and [[Nintendo Switch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/news/animal-crossing-on-nintendo-switch|title=Animal Crossing on Nintendo Switch: release date, news and features|last=Hood|first=Vic|last2=Gaming|first2=Nick Pino 2019-06-18T17:06:19Z|website=TechRadar|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> The series has been both critically and commercially successful and has sold over 30 million units worldwide. Three spin-off games have also been released: ''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer]]'' for [[Nintendo 3DS]], ''[[Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival]]'' for [[Wii U]], and ''[[Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp]]'' for mobile devices.\n\n== Common elements ==\n\n=== Characters ===\n{{main|Characters in the Animal Crossing series}}\nWhile the series features various villagers for each title, certain prominent characters return in each series installment. [[Tom Nook]] is a [[Japanese raccoon dog|tanuki]] character who functions as both a shop owner and real estate broker, giving the player a loan for their house and allowing them to pay it back with no interest. He is one of the only residents of the town to follow a [[Capitalism|capitalist]] ethos. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/tom-nook-needs-to-get-with-the-times-1829149177|title=Tom Nook Needs To Get With The Times|last=Jackson|first=Gita|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> [[Mr. Resetti]] is a mole character who appears from underground whenever players shut off the game without saving, berating them for circumventing one of the game's systems. Due to a new [[autosave]] function, he was \"laid off\" from his job in ''Animal Crossing: New Horizons'', although he has gotten a new job as the Rescue Service operator. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2019/06/17/animal-crossing-new-horizons-autosave-resettis-job/|title=Animal Crossing New Horizons has autosave, so Resetti's out of a job|date=2019-06-17|website=VG247|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n[[K.K. Slider]] is a canine traveling musician based on series composer [[Kazumi Totaka]], and plays on certain nights in the town's club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/05/profile_kazumi_totaka_the_man_behind_animal_crossings_kk_slider|title=Profile: Kazumi Totaka - The Man Behind Animal Crossing's K.K. Slider|last=Life|first=Nintendo|date=2013-05-08|website=Nintendo Life|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> Afterwards, he gifts the player a free copy of the song played, saying that his music \"wants to be free\". This was seen by some fans as tacit support for [[music piracy]], although Nintendo denied that it was intended as [[social commentary]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/19/technology/social-commentary-or-just-a-dogs-opinion.html|title=Social Commentary, or Just a Dog's Opinion?|last=Jr|first=Tom Zeller|date=2005-12-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Gameplay===\nIn the ''Animal Crossing'' games, the player assumes the role of a human child, aged between 9-13, who moves into a rural village populated with anthropomorphic animals and lives there indefinitely. Gameplay is [[Nonlinear gameplay|open-ended]]: players have no defined objectives, but are instead encouraged to spend their time in the village performing any number of activities, which include collecting items, planting plants or other items, and socializing with the village's residents. ''Animal Crossing'' games are played in [[Real time (media)|real time]], utilizing the [[video game console]]'s internal clock and calendar. Thus, passage of time in the game world reflects that in reality, as well as the current season and time of day. Some in-game events, such as holidays or the growth of a tree, occur at certain times or require some duration of time to have passed.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_preview\"/>\n\nOne notable feature of the ''Animal Crossing'' series is the high level of customization available, some of which affects the outcome of the game.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\" /> The [[player character]] is both named and gendered by the real life player at the start of the game, and their appearance can be modified by buying or designing custom clothes and accessories or changing the hairstyle (introduced in ''[[Animal Crossing: Wild World|Wild World]]''). The player's house can also be furnished, decorated, and later expanded: the player can purchase and collect furniture and place it anywhere in the house, as well as change both the wallpaper and floor designs. While its terrain, building locations, and initial residents are randomly generated when the game is first begun (except in ''Animal Crossing: New Leaf'', in which the player decides between four given towns, and ''Animal Crossing: New Horizons'', in which the player similarly decides between four given islands), the village's name and anthem, as well as some of the residents' catchphrases, are also determined by the player.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\"/>\n\nCollecting items is a major facet of ''Animal Crossing'': the player can explore the village and gather objects, including fruit from trees, seashells, and discarded items. Nearly all objects can be sold for Bells, the in-game currency. Players collect objects to obtain more Bells, which can then be used to buy furniture and clothing, purchase home expansions, invest in stocks, and play games. A number of specialized tools are available for other activities such as fishing and insect collecting. Special items, such as fossils and paintings, may be donated to the village museum. The player can choose to socialize with the other animal residents by engaging in conversation, sending and receiving letters, bartering, or playing hide-and-seek. Residents may move in or out of the village depending on the player's actions.\n\nAll installments of ''Animal Crossing'' allow some form of communication between players, both offline and [[Online game|online]]. A single village can house up to four human players, though only one can be exploring the village at any given time.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_preview\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing Preview |last=Schneider |first=Peer |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/05/30/animal-crossing |date=May 30, 2002 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The players can interact via written messages through the village post office or bulletin board. The [[GameCube]] iteration allowed players to travel to other villages by trading [[Nintendo GameCube#Memory and storage|memory cards]] written with the game data,<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\"/> but all subsequent installments allow players to travel and interact online via [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection]], although ''[[Animal Crossing: City Folk|City Folk]]'' also allows the DS Suitcase to travel to others' towns.<ref name=\"IGN_DS_review\"/><ref name=\"IGN_Wii_review\"/>\n\n==Games==\n\n{{Timeline of release years\n| summary = Timeline of releases in the ''Animal Crossing'' series, from 2001 to present.\n| range1       = 2001 \u2013\n| range1_color = #ffc836 #e5d2ac <!-- Based on series logo -->\n| 2001 = ''[[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]''\n| 2005 = ''[[Animal Crossing: Wild World|Wild World]]''\n| 2008 = ''[[Animal Crossing: City Folk|City Folk]]''\n| 2012 = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf|New Leaf]]''\n| 2015a = ''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer|Happy Home Designer]]''\n| 2015b = ''[[Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival|Amiibo Festival]]''\n| 2016 = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf|New Leaf \u2013 Welcome Amiibo]]''\n| 2017 = ''[[Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp|Pocket Camp]]''\n| 2020 = ''[[Animal Crossing: New Horizons|New Horizons]]''\n}}\n\n===Main series===\n\n====''Animal Crossing'' (2001)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing (video game)}}\n''Animal Crossing''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Animal Forest''}}}} was originally released in Japan for the [[Nintendo 64]] on April 14, 2001. It was enhanced and released on the [[GameCube]] the same year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/13/the-evolution-of-animal-crossing-2?page=2 |title=The Evolution of Animal Crossing (page 2) |last=Harris |first=Craig |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> This version was localized and released in North America on September 16, 2002, Australia on October 17, 2003, and Europe on September 24, 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/action-replay-ultimate-codes-animal-crossing/gcn-16562 |title=Animal Crossing Review |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> An extended version titled \"D\u014dbutsu no Mori e+\" was released on June 27, 2003 in Japan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/doubutsu-no-mori/gcn-552545 |title=Doubutsu no Mori e+ |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The Nintendo 64 version of the game was released in China in 2006 for [[iQue Player]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ique.com/games/21041.htm |title=Animal Forest |publisher=iQue Ltd. |language=Chinese |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Wild World'' (2005)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Wild World}}\n''Animal Crossing: Wild World''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Oideyo D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u304a\u3044\u3067\u3088 \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Come to Animal Forest''}}}} was released for the [[Nintendo DS]] in Japan on November 23, 2005, North America on December 5, 2005, Australia on December 8, 2005, and Europe on March 31, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/animal-crossing-wild-world/nds-682878 |title=Animal Crossing: Wild World Review |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was the first game in the series to use [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection]]. The game was later re-released on the [[Wii U]] [[Virtual Console]] on October 13, 2016, although its Wi-Fi multiplayer feature is unavailable due to the [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection#Closing|discontinuation]] of Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection.\n\n====''Animal Crossing: City Folk'' (2008)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: City Folk}}\n''Animal Crossing: City Folk'',{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Machi e Ik\u014d yo D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u8857\u3078\u884c\u3053\u3046\u3088 \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Let's Go to the City: Animal Forest''}}}} known as ''Animal Crossing: Let's Go to the City'' in Europe and Australia, was released for the [[Wii]] in North America on November 16, 2008, Japan on November 20, 2008, Australia on December 4, 2008, and Europe on December 5, 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/animal-crossing-city-folk/wii-748892 |title=Animal Crossing: City Folk Review |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was later released in South Korea in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendo.co.kr/Wii/software/animal_crossing/main.php |title=\ud0c0\uc6b4\uc73c\ub85c \ub180\ub7ec\uac00\uc694 \ub3d9\ubb3c\uc758 \uc232 |publisher=Nintendo |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |language=Korean}}</ref> It was the first Wii game to utilize the [[Wii Speak]], an accessory that allows players to talk to each other during online play.\n\n====''Animal Crossing: New Leaf'' (2012)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: New Leaf}}\n''Animal Crossing: New Leaf''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Tobidase D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u3068\u3073\u3060\u305b \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Jump Out Animal Forest''}}}} was announced at [[E3 2010]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/06/15/e3-2010-animal-crossing-3ds-announced|title=E3 2010: Animal Crossing 3DS Announced|publisher=IGN|last=Thomas|first=Lucas M.|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was released for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] in Japan on November 8, 2012, North America on June 9, 2013, Europe on June 14, 2013, and Australia on June 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/games/animal-crossing-3ds/3ds-77803 |title=Animal Crossing: New Leaf |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> For the first time in the series, players are appointed to the role of Mayor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/10/25/animal-crossing-3ds-has-a-new-name|title=Animal Crossing 3DS Has a New Name|last=Drake|first=Audrey|publisher=IGN|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\nIn November 2016, a new update was released along with \"Welcome Amiibo\" in North America and Europe, adding several new locations, items and activities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome Amiibo|url=http://www.mojenintendo.cz/animal-crossing-new-leaf-welcome-amiibocard/|website=mojenintendo.cz|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====''Animal Crossing: New Horizons'' (2020)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: New Horizons}}\nA game in the series for [[Nintendo Switch]] was announced in a [[Nintendo Direct]] in September 2018, later revealed as ''Animal Crossing: New Horizons''.{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Atsumare D\u014dbutsu no Mori''|\u3042\u3064\u307e\u308c \u3069\u3046\u3076\u3064\u306e\u68ee||lit. ''Gathering Animal Forest''}}}} Set on a deserted island, it was released on March 20, 2020 after initially being planned for release in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Plante |first1=Chris |title=Animal Crossing: New Horizons looks magical, but is delayed to March 2020 |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2019/6/11/18661310/nintendo-direct-e3-2019-animal-crossing-new-horizons-trailer-release-date |website=Polygon |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Spin-off games===\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer'' (2015)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer}}\n''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer]]'' is a [[Social simulation game|community simulation]] video game for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] and the first spin-off of the ''Animal Crossing'' series. It was released in Japan on July 30, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2015/05/animal-crossing-happy-home-designer-japanese-release-date-set|title=Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer Japanese release date set|last=Romano|first=Sal|publisher=Gematsu|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> North America on September 25, 2015,<ref name=\"meta-hhd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/animal-crossing-happy-home-designer|title=Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> Europe on October 2, 2015,<ref name=\"nwd-hhd\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/40828/animal-crossing-happy-home-designer-bundles-announced-for-uk-and-australia |title=Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer Bundles Announced for UK and Australia |publisher=Nintendo World Report |last=Abou-Nasr |first=Adam |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> and Australia on October 3, 2015.<ref name=\"nwd-hhd\" /> The game revolves around designing houses for villagers based on their requests. By scanning [[Amiibo]] cards, players can unlock the ability to design special characters' houses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/06/animal_crossing_director_talks_more_about_happy_home_designer_and_amiibo|title=Animal Crossing Director Talks More About Happy Home Designer and amiibo|publisher=Nintendo Life|last=Vogel|first=Mitch|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The game has a score of 66 out of 100 on [[Metacritic]], which signifies \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref name=\"meta-hhd\" />\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival'' (2015)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival}}\n''[[Animal Crossing: Amiibo Festival]]'' is a [[Party video game|party]] video game for the [[Wii U]] released in November 2015 that heavily utilizes [[Amiibo]]. It was met with unfavorable reviews from critics.<ref name=\"meta-af\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/animal-crossing-amiibo-festival/critic-reviews |title=Animal Crossing: amiibo Festival |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> It was developed by [[Nintendo Entertainment Planning & Development]] and [[NDcube]].\n\n====''Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp'' (2017)====\n{{main|Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp}}\nIn April 2016, Nintendo announced that an ''Animal Crossing'' mobile game, later named as ''[[Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp]]'', would be released as a part of their [[Nintendo mobile games|mobile game lineup]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Seedhouse|first1=Alex|title=Next Nintendo Apps Will Use Fire Emblem & Animal Crossing Franchises|url=http://www.nintendo-insider.com/2016/04/next-nintendo-apps-will-use-fire-emblem-animal-crossing-franchises/|website=Nintendo Insider|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The game was soft launched in Australia in October 2017, and released worldwide on November 21, 2017.\n\n===Apps===\n* ''[[Animal Crossing Plaza]]'', a [[Wii U system software#WaraWara Plaza|WaraWara Plaza]]-like app for [[Wii U]]. Limited time promotion for ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]''.\n* ''Animal Crossing Clock'', a Clock system app for [[Nintendo DSi]] and [[Nintendo 3DS]].\n* ''Animal Crossing Calculator'', a Calculator app for [[Nintendo DSi]] and [[Nintendo 3DS]].\n* ''Photos with Animal Crossing'', a Camera app for [[Nintendo 3DS]] allowing players to take photos with Animal Crossing characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nintendoeverything.com/photos-with-animal-crossing-nintendo-uk-summer-tour-2015-video/#disqus_thread|title=Photos with Animal Crossing - Nintendo UK Summer Tour 2015 video|work=Nintendo Everything|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\n{{Video game series reviews\n|updated = March 18, 2020\n|sales_title = Units sold<br />{{small|(in millions)}}\n\n|game1 = [[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]\n|year1 = 2001\n|sales1 = 2.32<ref name=\"GC_NA_sales\"/><ref name=\"GC_JP_sales\"/>\n|mc1 = 87/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/gamecube/animal-crossing |title=''Animal Crossing'' (GCN) at Metacritic |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |publisher=Metacritic.com}}</ref>\n\n|game2 = [[Animal Crossing: Wild World]]\n|year2 = 2005\n|sales2 = 11.75<ref name=\"DS_sales\"/>\n|mc2 = 86/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ds/animal-crossing-wild-world |title=Animal Crossing: Wild World |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|game3 = [[Animal Crossing: City Folk]]\n|year3 = 2008\n|sales3 = 3.38<ref name=\"Wii_sales\"/>\n|mc3 = 73/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii/animal-crossing-city-folk|title=''Animal Crossing: City Folk'' reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|game4 = [[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]\n|year4 = 2012\n|sales4 = 12.21<ref name =\"3DS-top-sell\"/>\n|mc4 = 88/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/animal-crossing-new-leaf |title=Animal Crossing: New Leaf |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|game5 = [[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]]\n|year5 = 2020\n|sales5 = 3.03 <ref> {{ cite web |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2020/04/japanese_charts_animal_crossing_new_horizons_surpasses_mario_kart_8_deluxe_lifetime_physical_sales |title=Japanese Charts: Animal Crossing: New Horizons Surpasses Mario Kart 8 Deluxe Lifetime Physical Sales |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|mc5 = 91/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/animal-crossing-new-horizons|title=Animal Crossing: New Horizons |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe ''Animal Crossing'' games have garnered positive response.<ref name=\"IGN_GC_review\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing Review |last=Schneider |first=Peer |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/09/05/animal-crossing-review |date=September 5, 2002 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN_DS_review\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing: Wild World Review |last=Harris |first=Craig |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/12/06/animal-crossing-wild-world |date=December 5, 2005 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN_Wii_review\">{{cite web| title=Animal Crossing: City Folk Review |last=Harris |first=Craig |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/17/animal-crossing-city-folk-review |date=November 16, 2008 |publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The first four main series games are among the [[List of best-selling video games|best-selling video games]] for their respective consoles. ''Animal Crossing'' has sold 2.32 million copies;<ref name=\"GC_NA_sales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-USPlatinum.shtml|title=US Platinum Videogame Chart|publisher=The Magic Box|accessdate=February 13, 2017|date= December 27, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"GC_JP_sales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-gamecharts.com/gc.php|title= Nintendo Gamecube Japanese Ranking|publisher= Japan Game Charts|date=May 6, 2007|accessdate=February 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070723025415/http://www.japan-gamecharts.com/gc.php|archive-date=July 23, 2007}}</ref> ''Wild World'' 11.75 million;<ref name=\"DS_sales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/sales/software/ds.html|title=Financial  Results Briefing for Fiscal Year Ended March 2014|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|date=December 6, 2014| format=PDF|accessdate=February 13, 2017|pages=6}}</ref> ''City Folk'' 3.38 million;<ref name=\"Wii_sales\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2009/090508e.pdf#page=6|title=Financial Results Briefing for the Fiscal Year Ended March 2009: Supplementary Information|accessdate=February 13, 2017|date=May 8, 2009|work=Financial Results Briefing for the 69th Fiscal Term Ended March 2009|publisher=Nintendo|pages=6}}</ref> ''New Leaf'' 12.21 million,<ref name =\"3DS-top-sell\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/sales/software/3ds.html|title=IR Information : Sales Data - Top Selling Software Sales Units - Nintendo 3DS Software|website=Nintendo|accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref> and ''Happy Home Designer'' 3.04 million.<ref name=\"HHD sales\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2016/160427_4e.pdf |title=Supplementary Information about Earnings Release |date=April 27, 2016 |publisher=Nintendo |page=4 |format=PDF |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> ''Amiibo Festival'' was a critical and commercial failure; in Japan it has only sold 26,325 copies.<ref name=\"meta-af\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/117/G011794/20151202067/ |title=\u300c\u30e2\u30f3\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30cf\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30af\u30ed\u30b9\u300d\u72e9\u731f\u89e3\u7981\u3067\u521d\u9031\u8ca9\u58f2\u6570148\u4e07\u672c\u306e\u300c\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u9031\u9593\u8ca9\u58f2\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\uff0b\u300d |work=[[4Gamer.net]] |publisher=Aetas Inc. |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |language=Japanese}}</ref> In total, the ''Animal Crossing'' franchise has sold over 30 million units.\n\n===Female demographic===\nFormer president of [[Nintendo]], [[Satoru Iwata]] noted that 56% of people who pre-ordered ''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]'' identified as female, with many of them purchasing a [[Nintendo 3DS]] specifically for the game. He found the game's success with adult women between the ages of 19 to 24 to be particularly noteworthy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2013/02/10/a-lot-of-women-bought-a-3ds-for-animal-crossing-new-leaf-in-japan/ |title=A Lot Of Women Bought A 3DS For Animal Crossing: New Leaf In Japan |website=Siliconera |date=February 10, 2013 |access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2013/01/08/satoru-iwata-on-animal-crossing-sales-56-of-players-are-female/ |title=Satoru Iwata On Animal Crossing Sales, 56% Of Players Are Female |website=Siliconera |date=January 8, 2013 |access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://mashable.com/2014/04/02/animal-crossing-gender-gaming/ |title=More Women Game Developers Means More Success, 'Animal Crossing' Director Says |website=Mashable |date=April 2, 2014 |access-date=September 17, 2018 |first=Chelsea |last=Stark}}</ref>\n\n===Hong Kong protests===\nDuring the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]], ''[[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]]'' was used by democracy activists in Hong Kong as a platform to protest. In reaction, the game, although not officially available in China, has been officially removed from online stores such as Taobao, but parallel import copies continue to remain on sale.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nintendo-china-animalcrossing/nintendo-game-pulled-from-chinese-platforms-after-hong-kong-protest-idUSKCN21S11F |title=Nintendo game pulled from Chinese platforms after Hong Kong protest |website=Reuters|date=April 10, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n[[File:Villager (character).png|thumb|The male Villager, as depicted in ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'']]\nAn [[anime]] [[film adaptation]] of ''Wild World'', titled ''[[D\u014dbutsu no Mori (film)|D\u014dbutsu no Mori]]'', was released in Japan on December 16, 2006. The film was produced by [[OLM, Inc.]] and distributed by [[Toho]]. ''D\u014dbutsu no Mori'' earned [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]]1.8 billion (approximately $19.2 million) in the [[box office]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.rakuten.co.jp/movie/ranking/boxoffice/2007/ |title=2007\u5e74\u5ea6\u8208\u884c\u6210\u7e3e\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 |language=Japanese |publisher=Rakuten |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121029165113/http://entertainment.rakuten.co.jp/movie/ranking/boxoffice/2007/ |archivedate=October 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the Wii game ''[[WarioWare: Smooth Moves]]'', released in Japan in 2006 and Europe, North America and Australia in 2007, there is a minigame that is modeled after Animal Crossing: Wild World, [[mariowiki:Animal Crossing: Wild World|under the same name]]. The player has to catch a fish using the same mechanics as the original game.\n\nThe 2008 Wii game ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]'' features elements from ''Wild World''. Most prominent is a stage based on the animal village, called \"Smashville\", which changes its scenery in accordance with the Wii system clock<ref name=\"smash_stage\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Smashville |date=July 13, 2007 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/stages/stage06.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> and features a number of [[Video game music|songs]] remixed or extracted from the original game.<ref name=\"smash_music\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Full Song List with Secret Songs |date=April 3, 2008 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/music/music24_list.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> Mr. Resetti and a pitfall seed, which appear in all ''Animal Crossing'' games, are available as an Assist Trophy and an item respectively.<ref name=\"smash_resetti\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Mr. Resetti |date=September 26, 2007 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/items/assist/assist08.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"smash_pitfall\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Pitfall |date=September 26, 2007 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/items/item06.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> ''Brawl'' also features 24 collectible trophies based on ''Animal Crossing'' characters and items.<ref name=\"smash_trophies\">{{cite web| last= Sakurai |first= Masahiro |title= Smash Bros. DOJO!! Trophy List |date=April 8, 2008 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/various/various36_list.html|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[Wii Music]]'' features two playable songs from ''Animal Crossing''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.destructoid.com/here-s-the-rest-of-the-wii-music-tracklist-108429.phtml |title=Here's the rest of the Wii Music tracklist |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=North |first=Dale |date=October 20, 2008 |work=[[Destructoid]]}}</ref>\n\nThe minigame \"Animal Crossing: Sweet Day\" in ''[[Nintendo Land]]'' is based on the ''Animal Crossing'' game series. The objective of the game is for the Wii Remote players (1-4), to gather large amounts of candy scattered around the area and store them in their head without getting caught by the Gatekeepers, who are controlled using the two Wii U GamePad analog sticks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/uk/products/nintendo-land-wii-u/review/2/ |title=Nintendo Land (Wii U) review |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=Petit |first=Carolyn |date=November 18, 2012 |work=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>\n\nA playable character called \"Villager\" represents the ''Animal Crossing'' series as a fighter in ''[[Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U]]'' and ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]''. The character has both male and female forms, which are selected when choosing the character. His or her moves include the ability to catch other players in a net and firing Lloid the gyroid as a missile.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2468841,00.asp |title=How to Beast With Villager, Mega Man in Super Smash Bros. 3DS Demo |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=Torres |first=Timothy |date=September 13, 2014 |work=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]}}</ref> Additionally, [[Isabelle (Animal Crossing)|Isabelle]] from ''New Leaf'' appears as an Assist Trophy,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wiiu-3ds/us/howto/entry6.html |title=Assist Trophies |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |work=[[Nintendo]]}}</ref> and later appeared as a standalone fighter in ''Ultimate''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/2018/09/13/super-smash-bros-ultimate-isabelle-animal-crossing/|title='Animal Crossing' Favorite Isabelle Joins 'Super Smash Bros. Ultimate' Roster|website=Comicbook.com}}</ref> Two new ''Animal Crossing'' stages appear in the games: \"Town & City\" from ''City Folk'' in the Wii U version, and \"Tortimer Island\" from ''New Leaf'' in the 3DS version.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smashbros.com/wiiu-3ds/us/howto/entry4.html |title=Stages 1 |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |work=[[Nintendo]]}}</ref> \"Smashville\" from ''Brawl'' returns in the Wii U version.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/super-smash-bros-4-unlock-guide-characters-stages-how-wii-u-3ds-connect-10-million-us-sales-614833 |title=Super Smash Bros 4: Unlock Guide -- Characters and Stages; How Wii U and 3DS Connect; 10 Million US Sales |accessdate=February 13, 2017 |last=Bhat |first=Aditya |date=October 22, 2014 |work=[[International Business Times]] |publisher=[[IBT Media]]}}</ref>\n\nVillager and Isabelle are playable characters in ''[[Mario Kart 8]]'' via downloadable content, along with a racetrack based on ''Animal Crossing'' and a cup named after the series known as the \"Crossing Cup\".<ref name=\"Franchises coming to MK8\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/zelda-f-zero-coming-to-mario-kart-8-1627150730|title=Zelda, Animal Crossing Coming to Mario Kart 8 |publisher=Kotaku | first=Luke | last=Plunkett |date=August 26, 2014 |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> The two racers, along with the ''Animal Crossing'' track, were also included in the [[Nintendo Switch]] version of the game, ''[[Mario Kart 8 Deluxe]]'' along with a racing suit based on the series for the [[Mii]]. In June 2015, Isabelle and Mr. Resetti-themed cosmetics were added as costumes options for the player's \"Palico\" companion in ''[[Monster Hunter 4 Ultimate]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/06/monster_hunter_4_ultimate_june_dlc_brings_animal_crossing_devil_may_cry_and_awesome_designs|title=Monster Hunter 4 Ultimate June DLC Brings Animal Crossing, Devil May Cry and Awesome Designs|work=Nintendo Life|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Video games|Japan}}\n*[[List of Animal Crossing media|List of ''Animal Crossing'' media]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.animal-crossing.com/}}\n\n{{Animal Crossing series}}\n{{Nintendo franchises}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Animal Crossing| ]]\n[[Category:Life simulation games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo franchises]]\n[[Category:Social simulation video games]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 2001]]\n[[Category:Video games about animals]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n", "name_user": "Funnyboi420", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eGameplay)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Animal_Crossing"}
{"title_page": "Eremophila dalyana", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of plant}}\n{{use Australian English|date=January 2016}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date= January 2016}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|name = Gidgee fuchsia bush\n|image = Eremophila dalyana.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Eremophila dalyana'' growing near [[Innamincka, South Australia|Innaminka]]\n|status_system = \n|status = \n|genus = Eremophila (plant)\n|species = dalyana\n|authority = [[Ferdinand von Mueller|F.Muell.]]<ref name=APC>{{cite web|title=''Eremophila dalyana''|url= https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/113152|publisher=Australian Plant Census|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n|synonyms_ref =  <ref name =\"Chinnock\" />\n|synonyms = \n* ''Pholidia dalyana'' <small> ([[Ferdinand von Mueller|F.Muell.]]) [[George Bentham|Benth.]]</small>\n* ''Bontia dalyana'' <small>(F.Muell.) [[Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]]</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Eremophila dalyana''''', commonly known as '''gidgee fuchsia bush''', '''desert fuchsia''' or '''ilpengk''' by [[Alyawarre]] people in the [[Utopia, Northern Territory|Utopia]] homeland in  [[Central Australia]], is a [[flowering plant]] in the figwort [[Family (biology)|family]], [[Scrophulariaceae]] and is [[Endemism|endemic]] to an area of central [[Australia]]. It is a broom-like shrub or small tree with thin leaves and pale pink to white flowers. It is found in south-western [[Queensland]], the extreme north east of [[South Australia]] and in a small area in the [[Northern Territory]].\n\n==Description==\n''Eremophila dalyana'' is a shrub or small tree which grows to a height of between {{convert|1 and 4|m|ft|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} and a width of up to {{convert|1.5|m|ft|sigfig=1|abbr=on}}. It has many erect branches giving the plant a broom-like appearance. Most parts of the plant are covered with silvery or greyish scales. The leaves are erect, arranged in opposite pairs, linear in shape, mostly {{convert|13-50|mm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} long, about {{convert|1|mm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} wide and have a curved hook on the end.<ref name=Chinnock>{{cite book|last1=Chinnock|first1=R.J. (Bob)|title=Eremophila and allied genera : a monograph of the plant family Myoporaceae|date=2007|publisher=Rosenberg|location=Dural, NSW|isbn=9781877058165|pages=441\u2013442|edition=1st}}</ref><ref name=eflora>{{cite web|title=''Eremophila dalyana''|url=http://www.flora.sa.gov.au/cgi-bin/speciesfacts_display.cgi?form=speciesfacts&family=&genus=Eremophila&species=dalyana&iname=&submit=Display|publisher=Electronic Flora of South Australia|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Boschen\">{{cite book|last1=Boschen|first1=Norma|last2=Goods|first2=Maree|last3=Wait|first3=Russell|title=Australia's eremophilas : changing gardens for a changing climate|date=2008|publisher=Bloomings Books|location=Melbourne|isbn=9781876473655|page=36}}</ref>\n\nThe flowers are usually borne singly in leaf axils on a stalk {{convert|4-8|mm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} long. There are 5 grey-green, triangular [[sepal]]s which are scaly on the outer surface, hairy on the inside and {{convert|1.5-3.5|mm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} long. The [[petal]]s are {{convert|18-26|mm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} long and joined at their lower end to form a tube.  The petal tube is a shade of pinkish lilac  to white on the outside and has pale yellow spots inside. The outside surface is scaly and the inside of the petal lobes is hairy but the inside of the tube is filled with soft hairs. The 4 stamens are fully enclosed within the tube. The main flowering time is from July to October and is followed by fruits which are cylinder-shaped, {{convert|9-18|mm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} long and have a papery covering.<ref name=\"Chinnock\" /><ref name=\"eflora\" />\n\n==Taxonomy and naming==\nThe species was first formally described by [[Ferdinand von Mueller]] in 1865 and the description was published in ''[[Fragmenta phytographiae Australiae]]''.<ref name=APNI>{{cite web|title=''Eremophila dalyana''|url= http://id.biodiversity.org.au/name/apni/113152|publisher=APNI|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=Mueller>{{cite book|last1=von Mueller|first1=Ferdinand|title=Fragmenta phytographiae Australiae (Volume 5)|date=1865|location=Melbourne|pages=22\u201323|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/7222#page/22/mode/1up|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> The [[Botanical name|specific epithet]] (''dalyana'') honours [[Dominick Daly|Sir Dominick Daly]], [[Governor of South Australia]] from 1862 to 1868.<ref name=\"Chinnock\" />\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n''Eremophila dalyana'' occurs in south-western Queensland and the extreme north east of South Australia. There is also a [[Disjunct distribution|disjunct]] population in the south-eastern Northern Territory. It usually grows in sandy soil in [[Acacia aneura|mulga]] and [[Acacia cambagei|gidgee]] communities.<ref name=\"Chinnock\" />\n\n==Uses==\n=== Indigenous medicine===\nThe Alyawarre people of the Utopia community regard this plant, which they call ilpengk to be a source of powerful medicines, which they use to treat respiratory complaints and skin complaints like [[scabies]].<ref name=Williams>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Cheryll J.|title=Medicinal Plants in Australia Volume 4 an Antipodean Apothecary.|date=2013|publisher=Rosenberg Publishing|location=Sydney|isbn=9781925078084|page=314}}</ref> The medicine is prepared by collecting leaves which are then ground into a paste, mixed with fat, boiled, strained and decanted.<ref name=ipengk>{{cite web|title=Utopia Bush Medicine Project|url=http://central.batchelor.edu.au/project/utopia-bush-medicine-project/|publisher=Batchelor Institute of Indigenous Tertiary Education|accessdate=5 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307063538/http://central.batchelor.edu.au/project/utopia-bush-medicine-project/|archive-date=7 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Horticulture===\nGidgee fuchsia bush is a very drought tolerant plant and flowers especially abundantly in the driest years. It is also long lived and some specimens have grown in gardens for more than 30 years. It is most easily grown from [[cutting (plant)|cuttings]] but in humid areas needs to be [[grafting|grafted]] onto ''[[Myoporum]]''. It is hardy in a wide range of soils, grows in full or filtered sunlight and tolerates frost when mature.<ref name=\"Boschen\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\nVideo showing how indigenous Australians collect and process ilpengk to produce medicine: https://web.archive.org/web/20160304065051/http://central.batchelor.edu.au/film/ilpengk-slideshow/\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15592607}}\n\n[[Category:Eremophila (plant)|dalyana]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1865]]\n[[Category:Flora of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Flora of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Northern Territory]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of plant}}\n{{use Australian English|date=January 2016}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date= January 2016}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|name = Gidgee fuchsia bush\n|image = Eremophila dalyana.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Eremophila dalyana'' growing near [[Innamincka, South Australia|Innaminka]]\n|status_system = \n|status = \n|genus = Eremophila (plant)\n|species = dalyana\n|authority = [[Ferdinand von Mueller|F.Muell.]]<ref name=APC>{{cite web|title=''Eremophila dalyana''|url= https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/113152|publisher=Australian Plant Census|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n|synonyms_ref =  <ref name =\"Chinnock\" />\n|synonyms = \n* ''Pholidia dalyana'' <small> ([[Ferdinand von Mueller|F.Muell.]]) [[George Bentham|Benth.]]</small>\n* ''Bontia dalyana'' <small>(F.Muell.) [[Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]]</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Eremophila dalyana''''', commonly known as '''gidgee fuchsia bush''', '''desert fuchsia''' or '''ilpengk''' by [[Alyawarre]] people in the [[Utopia, Northern Territory|Utopia]] homeland in  [[Central Australia]], is a [[flowering plant]] in the figwort [[Family (biology)|family]], [[Scrophulariaceae]] and is [[Endemism|endemic]] to an area of central [[Australia]]. It is a broom-like shrub or small tree with thin leaves and pale pink to white flowers. It is found in south-western [[Queensland]], the extreme north east of [[South Australia]] and in a small area in the [[Northern Territory]].\n\n==Description==\n''Eremophila dalyana'' is a shrub or small tree which grows to a height of between {{convert|1 and 4|m|ft|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} and a width of up to {{convert|1.5|m|ft|sigfig=1|abbr=on}}. It has many erect branches giving the plant a broom-like appearance. Most parts of the plant are covered with silvery or greyish scales. The leaves are erect, arranged in opposite pairs, linear in shape, mostly {{convert|13-50|mm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} long, about {{convert|1|mm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} wide and have a curved hook on the end.<ref name=Chinnock>{{cite book|last1=Chinnock|first1=R.J. (Bob)|title=Eremophila and allied genera : a monograph of the plant family Myoporaceae|date=2007|publisher=Rosenberg|location=Dural, NSW|isbn=9781877058165|pages=441\u2013442|edition=1st}}</ref><ref name=eflora>{{cite web|title=Eremophila dalyana|url=http://www.flora.sa.gov.au/cgi-bin/speciesfacts_display.cgi?form=speciesfacts&family=&genus=Eremophila&species=dalyana&iname=&submit=Display|publisher=Electronic Flora of South Australia|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Boschen\">{{cite book|last1=Boschen|first1=Norma|last2=Goods|first2=Maree|last3=Wait|first3=Russell|title=Australia's eremophilas : changing gardens for a changing climate|date=2008|publisher=Bloomings Books|location=Melbourne|isbn=9781876473655|page=36}}</ref>\n\nThe flowers are usually borne singly in leaf axils on a stalk {{convert|4-8|mm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} long. There are 5 grey-green, triangular [[sepal]]s which are scaly on the outer surface, hairy on the inside and {{convert|1.5-3.5|mm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} long. The [[petal]]s are {{convert|18-26|mm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} long and joined at their lower end to form a tube.  The petal tube is a shade of pinkish lilac  to white on the outside and has pale yellow spots inside. The outside surface is scaly and the inside of the petal lobes is hairy but the inside of the tube is filled with soft hairs. The 4 stamens are fully enclosed within the tube. The main flowering time is from July to October and is followed by fruits which are cylinder-shaped, {{convert|9-18|mm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} long and have a papery covering.<ref name=\"Chinnock\" /><ref name=\"eflora\" />\n\n==Taxonomy and naming==\nThe species was first formally described by [[Ferdinand von Mueller]] in 1865 and the description was published in ''[[Fragmenta phytographiae Australiae]]''.<ref name=APNI>{{cite web|title=''Eremophila dalyana''|url= http://id.biodiversity.org.au/name/apni/113152|publisher=APNI|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=Mueller>{{cite book|last1=von Mueller|first1=Ferdinand|title=Fragmenta phytographiae Australiae (Volume 5)|date=1865|location=Melbourne|pages=22\u201323|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/7222#page/22/mode/1up|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> The [[Botanical name|specific epithet]] (''dalyana'') honours [[Dominick Daly|Sir Dominick Daly]], [[Governor of South Australia]] from 1862 to 1868.<ref name=\"Chinnock\" />\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n''Eremophila dalyana'' occurs in south-western Queensland and the extreme north east of South Australia. There is also a [[Disjunct distribution|disjunct]] population in the south-eastern Northern Territory. It usually grows in sandy soil in [[Acacia aneura|mulga]] and [[Acacia cambagei|gidgee]] communities.<ref name=\"Chinnock\" />\n\n==Uses==\n=== Indigenous medicine===\nThe Alyawarre people of the Utopia community regard this plant, which they call ilpengk to be a source of powerful medicines, which they use to treat respiratory complaints and skin complaints like [[scabies]].<ref name=Williams>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Cheryll J.|title=Medicinal Plants in Australia Volume 4 an Antipodean Apothecary.|date=2013|publisher=Rosenberg Publishing|location=Sydney|isbn=9781925078084|page=314}}</ref> The medicine is prepared by collecting leaves which are then ground into a paste, mixed with fat, boiled, strained and decanted.<ref name=ipengk>{{cite web|title=Utopia Bush Medicine Project|url=http://central.batchelor.edu.au/project/utopia-bush-medicine-project/|publisher=Batchelor Institute of Indigenous Tertiary Education|accessdate=5 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307063538/http://central.batchelor.edu.au/project/utopia-bush-medicine-project/|archive-date=7 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Horticulture===\nGidgee fuchsia bush is a very drought tolerant plant and flowers especially abundantly in the driest years. It is also long lived and some specimens have grown in gardens for more than 30 years. It is most easily grown from [[cutting (plant)|cuttings]] but in humid areas needs to be [[grafting|grafted]] onto ''[[Myoporum]]''. It is hardy in a wide range of soils, grows in full or filtered sunlight and tolerates frost when mature.<ref name=\"Boschen\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\nVideo showing how indigenous Australians collect and process ilpengk to produce medicine: https://web.archive.org/web/20160304065051/http://central.batchelor.edu.au/film/ilpengk-slideshow/\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15592607}}\n\n[[Category:Eremophila (plant)|dalyana]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1865]]\n[[Category:Flora of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Flora of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Northern Territory]]\n", "name_user": "Gderrin", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDescription:italics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eremophila_dalyana"}
{"title_page": "Serengeti National Park", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|National park in Tanzania, Africa}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Serengeti National Park\n| iucn_category = II\n| photo = Serengeti-Landscape-2012.JPG\n| photo_caption = Landscape in Serengeti National Park\n| location = [[Tanzania]]\n| nearest_city =\n| embedded1 = {{designation list | embed=yes\n   | designation1 = WHS\n   | designation1_date = 1981 <small>(5th [[World Heritage Committee|session]])</small>\n   | designation1_type = Natural\n   | designation1_criteria = vii, x\n   | designation1_number = [https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/156 156]\n   | designation1_free1name = State Party\n   | designation1_free1value = [[Tanzania]]\n   | designation1_free2name = Region\n   | designation1_free2value = [[List of World Heritage Sites in Africa|Africa]]\n}}\n| map = Tanzania |relief=1\n| coordinates = {{coord|2|20|S|34|34|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| area_km2 = 14750\n| established = 1951\n| visitation_num = 350,000 per year<ref>{{cite web | url=http://dailynews.co.tz/index.php/local-news/8757-dar-registers-three-wonders | title=Dar registers \"three wonders\" | date=20 August 2012 | publisher=[[Daily News (Tanzania)]] | accessdate=28 January 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922172928/http://www.dailynews.co.tz/index.php/local-news/8757-dar-registers-three-wonders | archivedate=22 September 2012 }}</ref>\n| visitation_year =\n| governing_body = [[Tanzania National Parks Authority]]\n}}\n[[File:Serengeti National Park.svg|thumb|Serengeti National Park]]\n\nThe '''Serengeti National Park''' is a [[Tanzania|Tanzanian]] [[national park]] in the [[Serengeti|Serengeti ecosystem]] in the [[Mara Region|Mara]] and [[Simiyu Region|Simiyu]] regions.<ref>[http://www.ardhi.go.tz/sites/default/files/TANZANIA_0.pdf The official Map of Tanzania with New Regions and Districts, Ministry of Lands, Housing and Human Settlements Development, 21 September 2012]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapcarta.com/29284154/Map|title=Simiyu Region|publisher=|accessdate=22 October 2016}}</ref> It is famous for its year-long migration of over 1.5 million white-bearded (or brindled) [[wildebeest]] and 250,001 [[zebra]] and for its numerous [[Nile crocodile]] and [[honey badger]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:A group of lions on the tree in the Serengeti prairies.jpg|thumb|left|A group of lions in a tree on the Serengeti prairies.]]\nThe [[Maasai people]] had been grazing their livestock in the open plains of eastern [[Mara Region]], which they named \"endless plains,\" for around 200 years when the first European explorer, Austrian [[Oscar Baumann]], visited the area in 1892.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ntz.info/gen/n00051.html|title=Dr. Oscar Baumann|website=ntz.info}}</ref> The name \"Serengeti\" is an approximation of the word used by the Maasai to describe the area, ''siringet'', which means \"the place where the land runs on forever\".<ref name=\"NGM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/magazine/|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120629025350/http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0602/feature1/text4.html|url-status=dead|title=National Geographic Magazine|website=Magazine|archive-date=29 June 2012|access-date=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first American to enter the Serengeti, [[Stewart Edward White]], recorded his explorations in the northern Serengeti in 1913. He returned to the Serengeti in the 1920s and camped in the area around Seronera for three months. During this time, he and his companions shot 50 lions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ntz.info/gen/n00683.html|title=Stewart Edward White|website=ntz.info}}</ref>\n\nBecause the hunting of lions made them scarce, the British colonial administration made a partial [[game reserve]] of {{convert|800|acre|km2}} in the area in 1921 and a full one in 1929. These actions were the basis for Serengeti National Park,<ref name=\"NGM\"/> which was established in 1951.\n\nThe Serengeti gained more fame after the initial work of [[Bernhard Grzimek]] and his son Michael in the 1950s. Together, they produced the book and film ''[[Serengeti Shall Not Die]]'', widely recognized as one of the most important early pieces of nature conservation documentary.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\nTo preserve wildlife, the British evicted the resident Maasai from the park in 1959 and moved them to the [[Ngorongoro Conservation Area]]. There is still considerable controversy surrounding this move, with claims made of coercion and deceit on the part of the colonial authorities.<ref name=\"NGM\"/>\n\nThe park is Tanzania's oldest national park and remains the flagship of the country's tourism industry, providing a major draw to the Northern Safari Circuit encompassing [[Lake Manyara National Park]], [[Tarangire National Park]], [[Arusha National Park]] and the [[Ngorongoro Conservation Area]]. It has over 2,500 lions and more than 1  million wildebeest.\n\n==Geology==\nThe [[Basement complex]] consists of [[Archaen]] Nyanzian System greenstones (2.81-2.63 Ga in age), Archaean [[granite]]-[[gneiss]] [[pluton]]s (2.72-2.56 [[Giga annum|Ga]] in age), which were [[geologic uplift|uplifted]] 180 [[megaannum|Ma ago]]) forming [[koppie]]s and elongated hills, the [[Neoproterozoic]] [[Mozambique Belt]] consisting of [[quartzite]] or granite, and the Neoproterozoic Ikorongo Group, consisting of [[sandstone]], [[shale]] and [[siltstone]] that form linear ridges.  The southeast portion of the park contains [[Ngorongoro]] [[Neogene]]-aged [[volcanics]], and [[Oldoinyo Lengai]] [[Holocene]]-aged [[volcanic ash]].  The Grometi, Mara, Mbalageti, and Orangi rivers flow westward to Lake Victoria, while the Oldupai River flows eastward into the Olbalbal Swamps.<ref name=\"Scoon\">{{cite book |last1=Scoon |first1=Roger |title=Geology of National Parks of Central/ Southern Kenya and Northern Tanzania: Geotourism of the Gregory Rift Valley, Active Volcanism and Regional Plateaus |date=2018 |publisher=Springer |isbn=9783319737843 |pages=69\u201379}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe park covers {{convert|14,750|km2|sqmi}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbs.go.tz/takwimu/references/Tanzania_in_figures2012.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131126120431/http://www.nbs.go.tz/takwimu/references/Tanzania_in_figures2012.pdf|url-status=dead|title=Tanzania in figures 2012, National Bureau of Statistics, Ministry of Finance, June 2013, page 12|archivedate=26 November 2013}}</ref> of grassland plains, [[savanna]], riverine forest, and woodlands. The park lies in northwestern Tanzania, bordered to the north by the [[Kenya]]n border, where it is continuous with the [[Maasai Mara|Maasai Mara National Reserve]]. To the southeast of the park is the [[Ngorongoro Conservation Area]], to the southwest lies Maswa Game Reserve, to the west are the [[Ikorongo Game Reserve|Ikorongo]] and [[Grumeti Game Reserve]]s, and to the northeast and east lies the Loliondo Game Control Area. Together, these areas form the larger [[Serengeti|Serengeti ecosystem]].\n\nThe park is usually described as divided into three regions-\n\n*Serengeti plains: the almost treeless grassland of the south is the most emblematic scenery of the park. This is where the wildebeest breed, as they remain in the plains from December to May. Other hoofed animals - zebra, gazelle, impala, [[hartebeest]], [[topi]], buffalo, [[waterbuck]] - also occur in huge numbers during the wet season. \"Kopjes\" are granite florations that are very common in the region, and they are great observation posts for predators, as well as a refuge for [[hyrax]] and [[Pythonidae|pythons]].\n[[File:A hippopotamus walking on the grass land in Seregeti National Park in the morning.jpg|thumb|left|A hippopotamus walking on the grass land in Serengeti National Park in the morning]]\n*Western corridor: the black clay soil covers the savannah of this region. The Grumeti River and its gallery forests is home to [[Nile crocodiles]], [[patas monkey]]s, [[hippopotamus]], and [[martial eagle]]s. The migration passes through from May to July.\n[[File:Serengeti western corridor-1001.jpg|thumb|Wildebeest on the main highway of the Western Corridor]]\n*Northern Serengeti: the landscape is dominated by open woodlands (predominantly [[Commiphora]]) and hills, ranging from [[Seronera]] in the south to the Mara River on the Kenyan border. Apart from the migratory wildebeest and zebra (which occur from July to August, and in November), this is the best place to find [[elephant]], [[giraffe]], and [[dik dik]].\n\nHuman habitation is forbidden in the park with the exception of staff for the [[Tanzania National Parks Authority]], researchers and staff of the [[Frankfurt Zoological Society]], and staff of the various lodges, campsites and hotels. The main settlement is Seronera, which houses the majority of research staff and the park's main headquarters, including its primary [[Seronera Airstrip|airstrip]].\n\n==Wildlife==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2017}}\n[[File:ImpalaSerengetiNationalParkMar2011.jpg|thumb|upright|An impala in the park]]\n[[File:A leopard on the tree in the Serengeti Plain.JPG|thumb|left|An [[African leopard]] and her cub in a tree on the Serengeti Plain]]\n[[File:A cheetah in the Serengeti prairies.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Tanzanian cheetah]] in the Serengeti prairies]]\n[[File:Grey Crowned Crane, Serengeti National Park, Tanzania (2010).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Grey crowned crane]] in Serengeti National Park, Tanzania]]\n[[File:Serengeti-African-Elephants.JPG|thumb|left|A herd of elephants in the morning in Serengeti National Park]]\n[[File:A Hildebrandt's starling bird in the Serengeti National Park.jpg|thumb|A [[Superb starling]] in the Serengeti National Park]]\nThe park is worldwide known for its abundance of wildlife and high biodiversity. \n\nThe migratory - and some resident - [[blue wildebeest|wildebeest]], which number over 1.5 million individuals, constitute the largest population of big mammals that still roam the planet. They are joined in their journey through the Serengeti-Mara ecosystem by 200,000 [[plains zebra]], 300,000  [[Thomson's gazelle|Thomson's]]<ref name=animals>{{Cite news|title=What Birds To Watch In Serengeti National Park|url=https://animals.net/serengeti-national-park/|publisher=Animal Network|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=bushbuckltd>{{Cite news|title=Getting To Serengeti National Park|url=https://www.bushbuckltd.com/nationalpark/serengeti|publisher=bushbuckltd|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref> and [[Grant's gazelle]], and tens of thousands of [[topi]] and [[Coke's hartebeest]]. [[Masai giraffe]], [[waterbuck]], [[impala]], [[warthog]] and [[hippo]] are also abundant. Some rarely seen species of antelope are also present in Serengeti National Park, such as [[common eland]], [[klipspringer]], [[roan antelope]], [[bushbuck]], [[lesser kudu]], [[fringe-eared oryx]] and [[dik dik]].\n\nPerhaps the most popular animals among tourists are the Big Five, which include:\n\n*[[Panthera leo melanochaita|Lion]]: the Serengeti is believed to hold the largest population of lions in Africa due in part to the abundance of prey species. More than 3,000 lions live in this ecosystem.\n*[[African leopard]]: these reclusive predators are commonly seen in the Seronera region but are present throughout the national park with the population at around 1,000.<ref name=allafrica>{{Cite news|title=Tanzania: Concern As Serengeti Leopards Resort to Cannibalism|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201802260092.html|publisher=allafrica|accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n*[[African bush elephant]]: the herds have recovered successfully from population lows in the 1980s caused by [[poaching]], numbering over 5,000 individuals,<ref>{{cite web|vauthors=Mduma H, Musyoki C, Maliti Kyale D, Nindi S, Hamza K, Ndetei R, Machoke M, Kimutai D, Muteti D, Maloba M, Bakari S, Kohi E|title=Aerial Total Count of Elephants and Buffaloes in the Serengeti-Mara Ecosystem|url=https://www.kws.go.ke/kws/sites/default/files/Mara%20Elephant%20Count%20Report.pdf|publisher=WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature (Formerly World Wildlife Fund), Nairobi, Kenya|access-date=14 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909055741/http://www.kws.go.ke/kws/sites/default/files/Mara%20Elephant%20Count%20Report.pdf|archive-date=9 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and are particularly numerous in the northern region of the park. \n*[[Eastern black rhinoceros]]: mainly found around the [[kopjes]] in the centre of the park, very few individuals remain due to rampant poaching. Individuals from the Masai Mara Reserve cross the park border and enter Serengeti from the northern section at times. There's currently a small but stable population of 31 individuals left in the park.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Number of rhinos stabilizes in Serengeti National Park|url=http://www.china.org.cn/environment/2014-12/09/content_34263743.htm|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n*[[African buffalo]]: the most numerous of the Big Five, with around 53,000 individuals inside the park.\n\nCarnivores -aside from the Big Five- include the 225 [[cheetah]]<ref name=allafrica/> - which is widely seen due to the abundance of gazelle -, about 3,500 [[spotted hyena]]<ref name=allafrica/>, two species of [[jackal]]s, [[African golden wolf]], [[honey badger]], [[striped hyena]], [[serval]], seven species of [[mongoose]]s, two species of [[otter]]s and the [[East African wild dog]] of 300 individuals, which recently reintroduced (locally extinct since 1991)<ref>{{Cite news|title=Wild dogs of the Serengeti|url=https://africageographic.com/blog/wild-dogs-serengeti/|publisher=Africageographic|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=allafrica/>. \nApart from the safari staples, primates such as [[yellow baboon|yellow]] and [[olive baboon]]s and [[vervet monkey]], [[mantled guereza|black-and-white colobus]] are also seen in the gallery forests of the Grumeti River.<ref name=focusingonwildlife>{{Cite news|title=Serengeti primates|url=https://focusingonwildlife.com/news/serengeti-primates/|publisher=Focusing on Wildlife|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOther mammals include [[aardvark]], [[aardwolf]], [[bat-eared fox]], [[ground pangolin]], [[crested porcupine]], three species of [[hyrax]]es and [[cape hare]].\n\nSerengeti National Park has also great ornithological interest, boasting about more than 500 bird species<ref>{{Cite news|title=What Birds To Watch In Serengeti National Park|url=https://www.africatouroperators.org/tanzania/serengeti/birds-to-watch|publisher=africatouroperators|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Bird watching in Serengeti National Park|url=https://www.shadowsofafrica.com/enquiry-tour/|publisher=Shadows Of Africa|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=animals/><ref name=bushbuckltd/>; including [[Masai ostrich]], [[secretarybird]], [[kori bustard]]s, [[helmeted guineafowl]]s, [[Grey-breasted spurfowl]], [[southern ground hornbill]], [[Balearica|crowned crane]]s, [[marabou stork]]s, [[yellow-billed stork]], [[lesser flamingo]],  [[martial eagle]]s, [[lovebird]]s, [[oxpecker]]s, and many species of [[vulture]]s.\n\nReptiles in Serengeti National Park include [[Nile crocodile]], [[leopard tortoise]], [[serrated hinged terrapin]], [[Agama agama|rainbow agama]], [[Nile monitor]], [[chameleon]]s, [[African rock python|African python]], [[black mamba]]<ref name=animals/>, [[black-necked spitting cobra]], [[Bitis arietans|puff adder]].\n\nSince 2005, the protected area is considered a [[East African lion|Lion]] Conservation Unit together with [[Maasai Mara National Reserve]] and a lion stronghold in East Africa-<ref>{{cite book |author=IUCN Cat Specialist Group |year=2006 |title= Conservation Strategy for the Lion ''Panthera leo'' in Eastern and Southern Africa |publisher=IUCN |location=Pretoria, South Africa}}</ref><ref>M\u00e9sochina, P., Mbangwa, O., Chardonnet, P., Mosha, R., Mtui, B., Drouet, N. and Kissui, B. (2010). Conservation status of the lion (''Panthera leo'' Linnaeus, 1758) in Tanzania. Paris: SCI Foundation, MNRT-WD, TAWISA & IGF Foundation.</ref>\n\n==Administration and protection==\nBecause of its biodiversity and ecological significance, the park has been listed by the [[UNESCO|United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization]] as a [[World Heritage Site]]. As a [[national park]], it is designated as a [[IUCN Protected Area Management Categories|Category II protected area]] under the system developed by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]], which means that it should be managed, through either a legal instrument or another effective means, to protect the ecosystem or ecological processes as a whole.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\nThe administrative body for all parks in Tanzania is the [[Tanzania National Parks Authority]]. [[Myles Turner (park warden)|Myles Turner]] was one of the park's first game wardens and is credited with bringing its rampant poaching under control.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.serengeti.org/p_turner.html#top|title=Serengeti - Myles Turner|publisher=|accessdate=22 October 2016}}</ref> His autobiography, ''My Serengeti Years: The Memoirs of an African Game Warden'', provides a detailed history of the park's early years.\n\n\"Snapshot Serengeti\" is a science project by the [[University of Minnesota]] Lion Project, which seeks to classify over 30 species of animals within the park using 225 [[camera trap]]s to better understand how they interact with each other and lions.<ref>{{cite web | title=Snapshot Serengeti | url=http://www.snapshotserengeti.org | accessdate= 12 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed road across the northern Serengeti==\n\nIn July 2010, President [[Jakaya Kikwete]] renewed his support for an upgraded road through the northern portion of the park to link [[Mto wa Mbu]], southeast of [[Ngorongoro Crater]], and [[Musoma]] on [[Lake Victoria]]. While he said that the road would lead to much-needed development in poor communities, others, including conservation groups and foreign governments like [[Kenya]], argued that the road could irreparably damage the [[Serengeti#Great migration|great migration]] and the park's ecosystem.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/31/world/africa/31serengeti.html|title=Tanzania Road Plan in Serengeti Offers Prospects and Fears|first=Jeffrey|last=Gettleman|date=30 October 2010|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.starafrica.com/news/serengeti-highway-threatens-great-migrat-118700.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728084438/http://en.starafrica.com/news/serengeti-highway-threatens-great-migrat-118700.html|url-status=dead|title=\"Serengeti Highway threatens great migration\", ''Agence France-Presse'', reported by Francois Ausseill, reprinted at ''StarAfrica.com'', 29 October 2010|archivedate=28 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Corporate%20News/Controversy%20over%20Serengeti%20road%20plan%20deepens/-/539550/1027510/-/item/0/-/q0xaavz/-/index|title=Controversy over Serengeti road plan deepens - Business Daily}}</ref>\n\nThe African Network for Animal Welfare sued the Tanzanian government in December 2010 at the [[East African Court of Justice]] in [[Arusha]] to prevent the road project. The court ruled in June 2014 that the plan to build the road was unlawful because it would infringe the [[East African Community Treaty]] under which member countries must respect protocols on conservation, protection, and management of natural resources. The court, therefore, restrained the government from going ahead with the project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/national/Tanzania-loses-Serengeti-road-case-/1840392-2356486-38y6qsz/index.html|title=Tanzania loses Serengeti road case|website=The Citizen}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed extension of park boundaries to Lake Victoria==\n\nGovernment officials have  proposed expanding the Serengeti National Park to reach [[Lake Victoria]] because increasingly intense droughts are threatening the survival of millions of animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-foundation-climatechange-serengeti-idUSKBN0HA0W320140915|title=Thirsty Serengeti wildlife to get new water hole: Lake Victoria|date=15 September 2014|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Citation |last=Homewood |first=K. W. |lastauthoramp=yes |last2=Rodgers |first2=W. A. |title=Maasailand Ecology: Pastoralist Development and Wildlife Conservation in Ngorongoro, Tanzania |location=New York |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1991 |isbn=0-521-40002-3 }}.\n*{{Citation |last=Turner |first=Myles |title=My Serengeti Years: the Memoirs of an African Games Warden |location=New York |publisher=W. W. Norton |year=1988 |isbn=0-393-02576-4 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/myserengetiyears00myle }}.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Serengeti National Park}}\n\n* [http://www.natgeotv.com/asia/super-pride Super Pride - National Geographic Channel] \n*[https://www.serengeti.com Serengeti Official website]\n* https://www.serengetinationalparktz.com/ Serengeti National park portal\n* [https://archive.is/19970710092414/http://www.wcmc.org.uk/protected_areas/data/wh/serenget.html/ WCMC World Heritage Site  - Serengeti]\n* [http://www.safarimappers.com/area.aspx?lngareaid=27 Map of Serengeti National Park]\n\n{{World Heritage Sites in Tanzania}}\n{{National Parks of Tanzania}}\n\n[[Category:1951 establishments in Tanganyika]]\n[[Category:Biosphere reserves of Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Geography of Mara Region]]\n[[Category:National parks of Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1951]]\n[[Category:Serengeti volcanic grasslands]]\n[[Category:Simiyu Region]]\n[[Category:Southern Acacia-Commiphora bushlands and thickets]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the Mara Region]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Tanzania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|National park in Tanzania, Africa}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Serengeti National Park\n| iucn_category = II\n| photo = Serengeti-Landscape-2012.JPG\n| photo_caption = Landscape in Serengeti National Park\n| location = [[Tanzania]]\n| nearest_city =\n| embedded1 = {{designation list | embed=yes\n   | designation1 = WHS\n   | designation1_date = 1981 <small>(5th [[World Heritage Committee|session]])</small>\n   | designation1_type = Natural\n   | designation1_criteria = vii, x\n   | designation1_number = [https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/156 156]\n   | designation1_free1name = State Party\n   | designation1_free1value = [[Tanzania]]\n   | designation1_free2name = Region\n   | designation1_free2value = [[List of World Heritage Sites in Africa|Africa]]\n}}\n| map = Tanzania |relief=1\n| coordinates = {{coord|2|20|S|34|34|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| area_km2 = 14750\n| established = 1951\n| visitation_num = 350,000 per year<ref>{{cite web | url=http://dailynews.co.tz/index.php/local-news/8757-dar-registers-three-wonders | title=Dar registers \"three wonders\" | date=20 August 2012 | publisher=[[Daily News (Tanzania)]] | accessdate=28 January 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922172928/http://www.dailynews.co.tz/index.php/local-news/8757-dar-registers-three-wonders | archivedate=22 September 2012 }}</ref>\n| visitation_year =\n| governing_body = [[Tanzania National Parks Authority]]\n}}\n[[File:Serengeti National Park.svg|thumb|Serengeti National Park]]\n\nThe '''Serengeti National Park''' is a [[Tanzania|Tanzanian]] [[national park]] in the [[Serengeti|Serengeti ecosystem]] in the [[Mara Region|Mara]] and [[Simiyu Region|Simiyu]] regions.<ref>[http://www.ardhi.go.tz/sites/default/files/TANZANIA_0.pdf The official Map of Tanzania with New Regions and Districts, Ministry of Lands, Housing and Human Settlements Development, 21 September 2012]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapcarta.com/29284154/Map|title=Simiyu Region|publisher=|accessdate=22 October 2016}}</ref> It is famous for its year-long migration of over 1.5 million white-bearded (or brindled) [[wildebeest]] and 250,001 [[zebra]] and for its numerous [[Nile crocodile]] and [[honey badger]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:A group of lions on the tree in the Serengeti prairies.jpg|thumb|left|A group of lions in a tree on the Serengeti prairies.]]\nThe [[Maasai people]] had been grazing their livestock in the open plains of eastern [[Mara Region]], which they named \"endless plains,\" for around 200 years when the first European explorer, Austrian [[Oscar Baumann]], visited the area in 1892.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ntz.info/gen/n00051.html|title=Dr. Oscar Baumann|website=ntz.info}}</ref> The name \"Serengeti\" is an approximation of the word used by the Maasai to describe the area, ''siringet'', which means \"the place where the land runs on forever\".<ref name=\"NGM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/magazine/|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120629025350/http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0602/feature1/text4.html|url-status=dead|title=National Geographic Magazine|website=Magazine|archive-date=29 June 2012|access-date=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first American to enter the Serengeti, [[Stewart Edward White]], recorded his explorations in the northern Serengeti in 1913. He returned to the Serengeti in the 1920s and camped in the area around Seronera for three months. During this time, he and his companions shot 50 lions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ntz.info/gen/n00683.html|title=Stewart Edward White|website=ntz.info}}</ref>\n\nBecause the hunting of lions made them scarce, the British colonial administration made a partial [[game reserve]] of {{convert|800|acre|km2}} in the area in 1921 and a full one in 1929. These actions were the basis for Serengeti National Park,<ref name=\"NGM\"/> which was established in 1951.\n\nThe Serengeti gained more fame after the initial work of [[Bernhard Grzimek]] and his son Michael in the 1950s. Together, they produced the book and film ''[[Serengeti Shall Not Die]]'', widely recognized as one of the most important early pieces of nature conservation documentary.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\nTo preserve wildlife, the British evicted the resident Maasai from the park in 1959 and moved them to the [[Ngorongoro Conservation Area]]. There is still considerable controversy surrounding this move, with claims made of coercion and deceit on the part of the colonial authorities.<ref name=\"NGM\"/>\n\nThe park is Tanzania's oldest national park and remains the flagship of the country's tourism industry, providing a major draw to the Northern Safari Circuit encompassing [[Lake Manyara National Park]], [[Tarangire National Park]], [[Arusha National Park]] and the [[Ngorongoro Conservation Area]]. It has over 2,500 lions and more than 1  million wildebeest.\n\n==Geology==\nThe [[Basement complex]] consists of [[Archaen]] Nyanzian System greenstones (2.81-2.63 Ga in age), Archaean [[granite]]-[[gneiss]] [[pluton]]s (2.72-2.56 [[Giga annum|Ga]] in age), which were [[geologic uplift|uplifted]] 180 [[megaannum|Ma ago]]) forming [[koppie]]s and elongated hills, the [[Neoproterozoic]] [[Mozambique Belt]] consisting of [[quartzite]] or granite, and the Neoproterozoic Ikorongo Group, consisting of [[sandstone]], [[shale]] and [[siltstone]] that form linear ridges.  The southeast portion of the park contains [[Ngorongoro]] [[Neogene]]-aged [[volcanics]], and [[Oldoinyo Lengai]] [[Holocene]]-aged [[volcanic ash]].  The Grometi, Mara, Mbalageti, and Orangi rivers flow westward to Lake Victoria, while the Oldupai River flows eastward into the Olbalbal Swamps.<ref name=\"Scoon\">{{cite book |last1=Scoon |first1=Roger |title=Geology of National Parks of Central/ Southern Kenya and Northern Tanzania: Geotourism of the Gregory Rift Valley, Active Volcanism and Regional Plateaus |date=2018 |publisher=Springer |isbn=9783319737843 |pages=69\u201379}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe park covers {{convert|14,750|km2|sqmi}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbs.go.tz/takwimu/references/Tanzania_in_figures2012.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131126120431/http://www.nbs.go.tz/takwimu/references/Tanzania_in_figures2012.pdf|url-status=dead|title=Tanzania in figures 2012, National Bureau of Statistics, Ministry of Finance, June 2013, page 12|archivedate=26 November 2013}}</ref> of grassland plains, [[savanna]], riverine forest, and woodlands. The park lies in northwestern Tanzania, bordered to the north by the [[Kenya]]n border, where it is continuous with the [[Maasai Mara|Maasai Mara National Reserve]]. To the southeast of the park is the [[Ngorongoro Conservation Area]], to the southwest lies Maswa Game Reserve, to the west are the [[Ikorongo Game Reserve|Ikorongo]] and [[Grumeti Game Reserve]]s, and to the northeast and east lies the Loliondo Game Control Area. Together, these areas form the larger [[Serengeti|Serengeti ecosystem]].\n\nThe park is usually described as divided into three regions-\n\n*Serengeti plains: the almost treeless grassland of the south is the most emblematic scenery of the park. This is where the wildebeest breed, as they remain in the plains from December to May. Other hoofed animals - zebra, gazelle, impala, [[hartebeest]], [[topi]], buffalo, [[waterbuck]] - also occur in huge numbers during the wet season. \"Kopjes\" are granite florations that are very common in the region, and they are great observation posts for predators, as well as a refuge for [[hyrax]] and [[Pythonidae|pythons]].\n[[File:A hippopotamus walking on the grass land in Seregeti National Park in the morning.jpg|thumb|left|A hippopotamus walking on the grass land in Serengeti National Park in the morning]]\n*Western corridor: the black clay soil covers the savannah of this region. The Grumeti River and its gallery forests is home to [[Nile crocodiles]], [[patas monkey]]s, [[hippopotamus]], and [[martial eagle]]s. The migration passes through from May to July.\n[[File:Serengeti western corridor-1001.jpg|thumb|Wildebeest on the main highway of the Western Corridor]]\n*Northern Serengeti: the landscape is dominated by open woodlands (predominantly [[Commiphora]]) and hills, ranging from [[Seronera]] in the south to the Mara River on the Kenyan border. Apart from the migratory wildebeest and zebra (which occur from July to August, and in November), this is the best place to find [[elephant]], [[giraffe]], and [[dik dik]].\n\nHuman habitation is forbidden in the park with the exception of staff for the [[Tanzania National Parks Authority]], researchers and staff of the [[Frankfurt Zoological Society]], and staff of the various lodges, campsites and hotels. The main settlement is Seronera, which houses the majority of research staff and the park's main headquarters, including its primary [[Seronera Airstrip|airstrip]].\n\n==Wildlife==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2017}}\n[[File:ImpalaSerengetiNationalParkMar2011.jpg|thumb|upright|An impala in the park]]\n[[File:A leopard on the tree in the Serengeti Plain.JPG|thumb|left|An [[African leopard]] and her cub in a tree on the Serengeti Plain]]\n[[File:A cheetah in the Serengeti prairies.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Tanzanian cheetah]] in the Serengeti prairies]]\n[[File:Grey Crowned Crane, Serengeti National Park, Tanzania (2010).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Grey crowned crane]] in Serengeti National Park, Tanzania]]\n[[File:Serengeti-African-Elephants.JPG|thumb|left|A herd of elephants in the morning in Serengeti National Park]]\n[[File:A Hildebrandt's starling bird in the Serengeti National Park.jpg|thumb|A [[Superb starling]] in the Serengeti National Park]]\nThe park is worldwide known for its abundance of wildlife and high biodiversity. \n\nThe migratory - and some resident - [[blue wildebeest|wildebeest]], which number over 1.5 million individuals, constitute the largest population of big mammals that still roam the planet. They are joined in their journey through the Serengeti-Mara ecosystem by 200,000 [[plains zebra]], 300,000  [[Thomson's gazelle|Thomson's]]<ref name=animals>{{Cite news|title=What Birds To Watch In Serengeti National Park|url=https://animals.net/serengeti-national-park/|publisher=Animal Network|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=bushbuckltd>{{Cite news|title=Getting To Serengeti National Park|url=https://www.bushbuckltd.com/nationalpark/serengeti|publisher=bushbuckltd|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref> and [[Grant's gazelle]], and tens of thousands of [[topi]] and [[Coke's hartebeest]]. [[Masai giraffe]], [[waterbuck]], [[impala]], [[warthog]] and [[hippo]] are also abundant. Some rarely seen species of antelope are also present in Serengeti National Park, such as [[common eland]], [[klipspringer]], [[roan antelope]], [[bushbuck]], [[lesser kudu]], [[fringe-eared oryx]] and [[dik dik]].\n\nPerhaps the most popular animals among tourists are the Big Five, which include:\n\n*[[Panthera leo melanochaita|Lion]]: the Serengeti is believed to hold the largest population of lions in Africa due in part to the abundance of prey species. More than 3,000 lions live in this ecosystem.\n*[[African leopard]]: these reclusive predators are commonly seen in the Seronera region but are present throughout the national park with the population at around 1,000.<ref name=allafrica>{{Cite news|title=Tanzania: Concern As Serengeti Leopards Resort to Cannibalism|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201802260092.html|publisher=allafrica|accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n*[[African bush elephant]]: the herds have recovered successfully from population lows in the 1980s caused by [[poaching]], numbering over 5,000 individuals,<ref>{{cite web|vauthors=Mduma H, Musyoki C, Maliti Kyale D, Nindi S, Hamza K, Ndetei R, Machoke M, Kimutai D, Muteti D, Maloba M, Bakari S, Kohi E|title=Aerial Total Count of Elephants and Buffaloes in the Serengeti-Mara Ecosystem|url=https://www.kws.go.ke/kws/sites/default/files/Mara%20Elephant%20Count%20Report.pdf|publisher=WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature (Formerly World Wildlife Fund), Nairobi, Kenya|access-date=14 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909055741/http://www.kws.go.ke/kws/sites/default/files/Mara%20Elephant%20Count%20Report.pdf|archive-date=9 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and are particularly numerous in the northern region of the park. \n*[[Eastern black rhinoceros]]: mainly found around the [[kopjes]] in the centre of the park, very few individuals remain due to rampant poaching. Individuals from the Masai Mara Reserve cross the park border and enter Serengeti from the northern section at times. There's currently a small but stable population of 31 individuals left in the park.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Number of rhinos stabilizes in Serengeti National Park|url=http://www.china.org.cn/environment/2014-12/09/content_34263743.htm|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n*[[African buffalo]]: the most numerous of the Big Five, with around 53,000 individuals inside the park.\n\nCarnivores -aside from the Big Five- include the 225 [[cheetah]]<ref name=allafrica/> - which is widely seen due to the abundance of gazelle -, about 3,500 [[spotted hyena]]<ref name=allafrica/>, two species of [[jackal]]s, [[African golden wolf]], [[honey badger]], [[striped hyena]], [[serval]], seven species of [[mongoose]]s, two species of [[otter]]s and the [[East African wild dog]] of 300 individuals, which recently reintroduced (locally extinct since 1991)<ref>{{Cite news|title=Wild dogs of the Serengeti|url=https://africageographic.com/blog/wild-dogs-serengeti/|publisher=Africageographic|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=allafrica/>. \nApart from the safari staples, primates such as [[yellow baboon|yellow]] and [[olive baboon]]s and [[vervet monkey]], [[mantled guereza|black-and-white colobus]] are also seen in the gallery forests of the Grumeti River.<ref name=focusingonwildlife>{{Cite news|title=Serengeti primates|url=https://focusingonwildlife.com/news/serengeti-primates/|publisher=Focusing on Wildlife|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOther mammals include [[aardvark]], [[aardwolf]], [[bat-eared fox]], [[ground pangolin]], [[crested porcupine]], three species of [[hyrax]]es and [[cape hare]].\n\nSerengeti National Park has also great ornithological interest, boasting about more than 500 bird species<ref>{{Cite news|title=What Birds To Watch In Serengeti National Park|url=https://www.africatouroperators.org/tanzania/serengeti/birds-to-watch|publisher=africatouroperators|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Bird watching in Serengeti National Park|url=https://www.shadowsofafrica.com/enquiry-tour/|publisher=Shadows Of Africa|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=animals/><ref name=bushbuckltd/>; including [[Masai ostrich]], [[secretarybird]], [[kori bustard]]s, [[helmeted guineafowl]]s, [[Grey-breasted spurfowl]], [[southern ground hornbill]], [[Balearica|crowned crane]]s, [[marabou stork]]s, [[yellow-billed stork]], [[lesser flamingo]],  [[martial eagle]]s, [[lovebird]]s, [[oxpecker]]s, and many species of [[vulture]]s.\n\nReptiles in Serengeti National Park include [[Nile crocodile]], [[leopard tortoise]], [[serrated hinged terrapin]], [[Agama agama|rainbow agama]], [[Nile monitor]], [[chameleon]]s, [[African rock python|African python]], [[black mamba]]<ref name=animals/>, [[black-necked spitting cobra]], [[Bitis arietans|puff adder]].\n\nSince 2005, the protected area is considered a [[East African lion|Lion]] Conservation Unit together with [[Maasai Mara National Reserve]] and a lion stronghold in East Africa-<ref>{{cite book |author=IUCN Cat Specialist Group |year=2006 |title= Conservation Strategy for the Lion ''Panthera leo'' in Eastern and Southern Africa |publisher=IUCN |location=Pretoria, South Africa}}</ref><ref>M\u00e9sochina, P., Mbangwa, O., Chardonnet, P., Mosha, R., Mtui, B., Drouet, N. and Kissui, B. (2010). Conservation status of the lion (''Panthera leo'' Linnaeus, 1758) in Tanzania. Paris: SCI Foundation, MNRT-WD, TAWISA & IGF Foundation.</ref>\n\n==Administration and protection==\nBecause of its biodiversity and ecological significance, the park has been listed by the [[UNESCO|United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization]] as a [[World Heritage Site]]. As a [[national park]], it is designated as a [[IUCN Protected Area Management Categories|Category II protected area]] under the system developed by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]], which means that it should be managed, through either a legal instrument or another effective means, to protect the ecosystem or ecological processes as a whole.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\nThe administrative body for all parks in Tanzania is the [[Tanzania National Parks Authority]]. [[Myles Turner (park warden)|Myles Turner]] was one of the park's first game wardens and is credited with bringing its rampant poaching under control.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.serengeti.org/p_turner.html#top|title=Serengeti - Myles Turner|publisher=|accessdate=22 October 2016}}</ref> His autobiography, ''My Serengeti Years: The Memoirs of an African Game Warden'', provides a detailed history of the park's early years.\n\n\"Snapshot Serengeti\" is a science project by the [[University of Minnesota]] Lion Project, which seeks to classify over 30 species of animals within the park using 225 [[camera trap]]s to better understand how they interact with each other and lions.<ref>{{cite web | title=Snapshot Serengeti | url=http://www.snapshotserengeti.org | accessdate= 12 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed road across the northern Serengeti==\n\nIn July 2010, President [[Jakaya Kikwete]] renewed his support for an upgraded road through the northern portion of the park to link [[Mto wa Mbu]], southeast of [[Ngorongoro Crater]], and [[Musoma]] on [[Lake Victoria]]. While he said that the road would lead to much-needed development in poor communities, others, including conservation groups and foreign governments like [[Kenya]], argued that the road could irreparably damage the [[Serengeti#Great migration|great migration]] and the park's ecosystem.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/31/world/africa/31serengeti.html|title=Tanzania Road Plan in Serengeti Offers Prospects and Fears|first=Jeffrey|last=Gettleman|date=30 October 2010|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.starafrica.com/news/serengeti-highway-threatens-great-migrat-118700.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728084438/http://en.starafrica.com/news/serengeti-highway-threatens-great-migrat-118700.html|url-status=dead|title=\"Serengeti Highway threatens great migration\", ''Agence France-Presse'', reported by Francois Ausseill, reprinted at ''StarAfrica.com'', 29 October 2010|archivedate=28 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Corporate%20News/Controversy%20over%20Serengeti%20road%20plan%20deepens/-/539550/1027510/-/item/0/-/q0xaavz/-/index|title=Controversy over Serengeti road plan deepens - Business Daily}}</ref>\n\nThe African Network for Animal Welfare sued the Tanzanian government in December 2010 at the [[East African Court of Justice]] in [[Arusha]] to prevent the road project. The court ruled in June 2014 that the plan to build the road was unlawful because it would infringe the [[East African Community Treaty]] under which member countries must respect protocols on conservation, protection, and management of natural resources. The court, therefore, restrained the government from going ahead with the project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/national/Tanzania-loses-Serengeti-road-case-/1840392-2356486-38y6qsz/index.html|title=Tanzania loses Serengeti road case|website=The Citizen}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed extension of park boundaries to Lake Victoria==\n\nGovernment officials have  proposed expanding the Serengeti National Park to reach [[Lake Victoria]] because increasingly intense droughts are threatening the survival of millions of animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-foundation-climatechange-serengeti-idUSKBN0HA0W320140915|title=Thirsty Serengeti wildlife to get new water hole: Lake Victoria|date=15 September 2014|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Citation |last=Homewood |first=K. W. |lastauthoramp=yes |last2=Rodgers |first2=W. A. |title=Maasailand Ecology: Pastoralist Development and Wildlife Conservation in Ngorongoro, Tanzania |location=New York |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1991 |isbn=0-521-40002-3 }}.\n*{{Citation |last=Turner |first=Myles |title=My Serengeti Years: the Memoirs of an African Games Warden |location=New York |publisher=W. W. Norton |year=1988 |isbn=0-393-02576-4 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/myserengetiyears00myle }}.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Serengeti National Park}}\n\n* [http://www.natgeotv.com/asia/super-pride Super Pride - National Geographic Channel] \n*[https://www.serengeti.com Serengeti Official website]\n* [https://archive.is/19970710092414/http://www.wcmc.org.uk/protected_areas/data/wh/serenget.html/ WCMC World Heritage Site  - Serengeti]\n* [http://www.safarimappers.com/area.aspx?lngareaid=27 Map of Serengeti National Park]\n\n{{World Heritage Sites in Tanzania}}\n{{National Parks of Tanzania}}\n\n[[Category:1951 establishments in Tanganyika]]\n[[Category:Biosphere reserves of Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Geography of Mara Region]]\n[[Category:National parks of Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1951]]\n[[Category:Serengeti volcanic grasslands]]\n[[Category:Simiyu Region]]\n[[Category:Southern Acacia-Commiphora bushlands and thickets]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the Mara Region]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Tanzania]]\n", "name_user": "154.230.134.20", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serengeti_National_Park"}
{"title_page": "KSPX-TV", "text_new": "{{short description|Ion Television station in Sacramento, California}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = KSPX-TV\n| city                     = Sacramento, California\n| station_logo             = \n| station_branding         = Ion Television\n| station_slogan           = ''Positively Entertaining''\n| digital                  = 48 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])<br>''(to move to 21 (UHF))''\n| virtual                  = 29 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| subchannels              = \n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = {{ION DTV/text|29}}'''[[KCSO-LD|33.2]]:''' [[Telemundo]]\n| owner                    = [[Ion Media|Ion Media Networks]]\n| licensee                 = {{nowrap|Ion Media Sacramento License, Inc.}}\n| location                 = [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]]\u2013[[Stockton, California|Stockton]]\u2013[[Modesto, California]]\n| country                  = United States\n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1990|8|27|p=y}}\n| enddate                  = \n| callsign_meaning         = '''S'''acramento's '''P'''a'''X''' TV\n| sister_stations          = \n| former_callsigns         = KRBJ (February\u2013March 1985)<br>KCMY (1985\u20131998)<br>KSPX (1998\u20132009)\n| former_channel_numbers   = '''Analog:'''<br>29 (UHF, 1990\u20132009)\n| former_affiliations      = [[Independent station (North America)|Independent]] (1990\u20131998)\n| effective_radiated_power = 48 [[kilowatt|kW]] ([[special temporary authority|STA]])<br>1,000 kW ([[construction permit|CP]])\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|228.6|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} (STA)<br>{{convert|444.6|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} (CP)\n| facility_id              = 52953\n| coordinates              = <br>{{nowrap|{{coord|38|14|50|N|121|30|7|W|type:landmark_scale:2000}}}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = {{URL|https://iontelevision.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''KSPX-TV''', [[virtual channel]] 29 ([[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 48), is an [[Ion Television]] [[owned-and-operated station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Sacramento, California]], United States. The station is owned by [[West Palm Beach, Florida]]-based [[Ion Media|Ion Media Networks]] (the former Paxson Communications). KSPX-TV's studio is located on Prospect Park Drive in [[Rancho Cordova, California|Rancho Cordova]], and its transmitter is located at TransTower in [[Walnut Grove, California|Walnut Grove]].\n\n==History==\nThe station first signed on the air on August 27, 1990 as '''KCMY'''; it originally operated as an [[Independent station (North America)|independent station]] with a general entertainment format. Paxson Communications purchased the station in 1998, changing its [[call signs in North America|call sign]] to '''KSPX'''. The station became a charter owned-and-operated station of its new Pax TV network (later i: Independent Television and now Ion Television) on August 31, 1998.\n\n==Digital television==\n\n{{ION DTV|29}}<ref>[http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=KSPX#station RabbitEars TV Query for KSPX]</ref>\n\nIn 2014, KSPX began simulcasting [[Telemundo]] affiliate [[KCSO-LD]] on digital subchannel 33.2.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming\n|-\n| | 33.2 || [[480i]] || [[16:9]] || TLMD || [[KCSO-LD]] / Telemundo\n|}\n\n===Analog-to-digital conversion===\nKSPX shut down its analog signal, over [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] channel 29, on June 12, 2009, as part of the [[Digital television transition in the United States|federally mandated transition from analog to digital television]].<ref name=\"Analog to Digital\">[http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf List of Digital Full-Power Stations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |date=2013-08-29 }}</ref> The station's digital signal remained on its pre-transition UHF channel 48, using [[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]] to display KSPX-TV's [[virtual channel]] as 29 on digital television receivers.\n\n===Reduced power operation===\nOn August 30, 2019, the station temporarily reduced power, per [[special temporary authority]] (STA), from 1,000 [[kilowatt|kW]] to 4.3 kW to accommodate relocation of its transmitter site.  \n\nPower was increased to 48 kW on November 16, 2019. The station will remain at this power level until May 1, 2020.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://iontelevision.com/}}\n*{{TVQ|KSPX}}\n*{{BIA|KSPX|TV|TV}}\n\n{{ION California}}\n{{Sacramento TV}}\n{{ION}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kspx-Tv}}\n[[Category:Ion Television affiliates]]\n[[Category:Telemundo subchannel-only network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1990]]\n[[Category:1990 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Sacramento, California|SPX-TV]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ion Television station in Sacramento, California}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = KSPX-TV\n| city                     = Sacramento, California\n| station_logo             = \n| station_branding         = Ion Television\n| station_slogan           = ''Positively Entertaining''\n| digital                  = 48 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])<br>''(to move to 21 (UHF))''\n| virtual                  = 29 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| subchannels              = \n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = {{ION DTV/text|29}}'''[[KCSO-LD|33.2]]:''' [[Telemundo]]\n| owner                    = [[Ion Media|Ion Media Networks]]\n| licensee   