l table==\nCorrected after balancing the data of the [[Olympic Council of Asia]] and other archived sites which had kept the previous Southeast Asian Games medal tables. Some information from the aforementioned sites are missing, incorrect and or not updated.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ocasia.org/Game/NocsMedalCount.aspx?SYCXGjC0df+J2ChZBk5tvA== |title=South East Asian Games Medal Count |access-date=31 August 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.seagfoffice.org/ SEAP Games Federation]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/19980111005738/http://seagames.wasantara.net.id/medali59-95/medals.htm Medal Tally 1959-1995]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20081011071000/http://www.newsviews.info/sport09.html#sources Medal Tally]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20041217101809/http://www.olympic.org.my/web/gamesrecords/sea/sea_history.htm History of the SEA Games]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091204132925/http://www.laoseagames2009.com/v1/seagamesxseapxstat.aspx SEA Games previous medal table]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20011207141223/http://www.kl2001.com/index.html SEA Games members]</ref>\n\n{{Medals table\n | caption        = All-time Southeast Asian Games medal table{{ref|1|[1]}}\n | host           = \n | flag_template  = flagSEAGFteam\n | event          = \n | team           = NOC\n | gold_THA = 1885 | silver_THA = 1930 | bronze_THA = 1943\n | gold_INA = 1824| silver_INA = 1703 | bronze_INA = 1780\n | gold_MAS = 1303 | silver_MAS = 1273 | bronze_MAS = 1685 | note_MAS = {{ref|2|[2]}}\n | gold_PHI = 1067 | silver_PHI = 1193 | bronze_PHI = 1477\n | gold_SGP = 947 | silver_SGP = 1002 | bronze_SGP = 1363\n | gold_VIE = 928 | silver_VIE = 967 | bronze_VIE = 991 | note_VIE = {{ref|3|[3]}}\n | gold_MYA = 564 | silver_MYA = 741 | bronze_MYA = 992 | note_MYA = {{ref|4|[4]}}\n | gold_LAO = 69 | silver_LAO = 93 | bronze_LAO = 319\n | gold_CAM = 69 | silver_CAM = 115 | bronze_CAM = 258 | note_CAM = {{ref|5|[5]}}\n | gold_BRU = 14 | silver_BRU = 55 | bronze_BRU = 163\n | gold_TLS = 3 | silver_TLS = 6 | bronze_TLS = 26\n}}\n<small>\n*{{note|1|[1]}} - [[2017 Southeast Asian Games]] medal counts are not yet included in these medal standings due to ongoing doping cases during those games\n*{{note|2|[2]}} \u2013 Competed as Malaya in the inaugural games until 1961.\n*{{note|3|[3]}} \u2013 The Republic of Vietnam was dissolved in July 1976 when it merged with the [[North Vietnam|Democratic Republic of Vietnam]] (North Vietnam) to become the [[Vietnam|Socialist Republic of Vietnam]], also known as Vietnam. Therefore, the medal counts for this country are considered to be as until 1975. In the 1989 edition, a unified Vietnam rejoined the games with a new name and flag. Medals won by South Vietnam are already combined here. The [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) does not use codes for South Vietnam anymore after the unification with North Vietnam.\n*{{note|4|[4]}} \u2013 Competed as Burma until 1987.\n*{{note|5|[5]}} \u2013 Competed as Kampuchea, and Khmer Republic.</small>\n\n==List of multiple Southeast Asian Games medalists==\n{{Main|List of multiple Southeast Asian Games medalists}}\nVarious individuals have won multiple medals at the Games, including the preceding Southeast Asian Peninsular Games. \n\nAs of 2019, Singaporean swimmer [[Joscelin Yeo]] has won the most Southeast Asian Games medals with 55 (40 gold, 12 silver, 3 bronze). She reached this milestone during the [[2005 Southeast Asian Games|2005 Games]], overtaking the previous record of 39 gold medals set by another Singaporean swimmer [[Patricia Chan]].\n\n==Criticism==\nThe games is unique in that it has no official limits to the number of sports to be contested, and the range can be decided by the organizing host pending approval by the Southeast Asian Games Federation. Aside from core sports that must be featured, the host is free to drop or introduce other events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/2103469/southeast-asian-games-yet-win-gold-sporting-spirit|title=Southeast Asian Games yet to win gold for sporting spirit|agency=[[South China Morning Post]]|author=Pattharapong Rattanasevee |date=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nThis leeway has resulted in hosts maximizing their medal hauls by dropping sports disadvantageous to themselves relative to their peers and the introduction of obscure sports, often at short notice, thus preventing most other nations from building credible opponents. Examples of these include:\n\n* At the [[2001 Southeast Asian Games]], Malaysia introduced [[p\u00e9tanque]], and [[netball]].\n* At the [[2003 Southeast Asian Games]], Vietnam added [[fin swimming]] and [[Jianzi|shuttlecock]], and had the wushu offer 28 golds from 16 in 2001.\n* In the [[2005 Southeast Asian Games]], the [[Philippines]] added [[Eskrima|arnis]], a demonstration sport in 2003, with six sets of medals, and it won three golds. Also added were baseball, dancesport and softball.\n* At the [[2007 Southeast Asian Games]], [[Thailand]] added categories of [[sepak takraw]] and used a new kind of ball used by its athletes for a year but never used by other countries. [[Futsal]] was also added. Thailand won nearly all medals in the event.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sports |url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/en/sports/5317/sea-games-or-a-village-festival.html |title=VietNamNet - SEA Games or a village festival &#124; SEA Games or a village festival |publisher=English.vietnamnet.vn |date= |accessdate=2 June 2011}}</ref>\n* In the [[2011 Southeast Asian Games]], [[Indonesia]] dropped the team events in table tennis and shrunk the medals offered in shooting to just 14 golds from 19 in 2009 and 33 in 2007. At the same time, [[Contract bridge|bridge]], [[kenp\u014d]], [[paragliding]], [[vovinam]] and [[Sport climbing|wall climbing]] were introduced.\n* In the [[2013 Southeast Asian Games]], [[Myanmar]] introduced its indigenous sport [[Chinlone]]. The host won six of eight gold medals in the event. [[Sittuyin]], a traditional form of Burmese chess that other competing nations were unfamiliar with, was included as a traditional chess number along with common [[chess]] competition number.<ref name=\"PhnomPenhPost\">{{cite web | url=http://www.phnompenhpost.com/sport/cambodia-eye-record-medal-haul | title=Cambodia eye record medal haul | author=HS Manjunath | publisher=The Phnom Penh Post | date=10 December 2013 | accessdate=13 December 2013}}</ref>\n* In the [[2017 Southeast Asian Games]], Malaysia introduced [[cricket]], [[indoor hockey]] and three [[Winter Olympics]] sports, namely [[figure skating]], [[short track speed skating]] and [[ice hockey]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.redbull.com/my-en/6-new-sports-watch-2017-sea-games|title=4 new sports we can now watch in 2017 SEA Games|work=Red Bull|access-date=2017-08-29|language=en}}</ref>\n* In the [[2019 Southeast Asian Games]], the [[Philippines]] added [[Beach handball|beach handball]], [[Duathlon|duathlon]], [[Esports|e-sports]], [[Jujutsu|jiu-jitsu]], [[Kickboxing|kickboxing]], [[Kurash|kurash]], [[sambo (martial art)|sambo]], [[Skateboarding|skateboarding]], [[Surfing|surfing]] and [[Wakeboarding|wakeboarding]] and [[Modern Pentathlon]] in non-Olympic format.\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* Events of the [[Olympic Council of Asia|OCA]] (Continental)\n** [[Asian Games]]\n** [[Asian Winter Games]]\n** [[Asian Youth Games]]\n** [[Asian Beach Games]]\n** [[Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games]]\n* Events of the [[Olympic Council of Asia|OCA]] (Regional)\n** [[East Asian Games]]\n** [[East Asian Youth Games]]\n** [[Central Asian Games]]\n** [[South Asian Games]]\n** [[West Asian Games]]\n{{col-2}}\n\n* Events of the [[Asian Paralympic Committee|APC]] (Continental)\n** [[Asian Para Games]]\n** [[Asian Youth Para Games]]\n\n* Events of the [[Asian Paralympic Committee|APC]] (Regional)\n** [[ASEAN Para Games]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ocasia.org/Game/GamesL1.aspx?GPCode=8 Olympic Council of Asia Regional Hosting List]\n* [http://www.seagfoffice.org/ SEA Games Federation]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/19980111005738/http://seagames.wasantara.net.id/medali59-95/medals.htm Medal Tally 1959-1995]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081011071000/http://www.newsviews.info/sport09.html#sources Medal Tally]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041217101809/http://www.olympic.org.my/web/gamesrecords/sea/sea_history.htm History of the SEA Games]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091204132925/http://www.laoseagames2009.com/v1/seagamesxseapxstat.aspx SEA Games previous medal table]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20011207141223/http://www.kl2001.com/index.html SEA Games members]\n\n{{Southeast Asian Multi Sports Events}}\n{{Sports at the Southeast Asian Games}}\n{{Nations at the Southeast Asian Games}}\n{{Southeast Asian Championships}}\n{{International multi-sport events}}\n{{EventsOCA}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Southeast Asian Games}}\n[[Category:Southeast Asian Games| ]]\n[[Category:Association of Southeast Asian Nations sports events]]\n[[Category:Asian international sports competitions]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1959]]\n[[Category:Multi-sport events in Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Biennial multi-sport event in Southeast Asia}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox sporting event organization\n|name = Southeast Asian Games\n|image = SEA_Games_logo.svg\n|caption = The [[Southeast Asian Games Federation]] logo\n|abbreviation = SEA Games\n|motto =\n|formation = [[1959 Southeast Asian Peninsular Games|1959 SEAP Games]] in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]\n|recurrence = 2 years (every odd year)\n|last = <!--DO NOT ADD ANYTHING HERE. It is only for games that are not active-->\n|purpose = Multi sport event for nations on the Southeast Asian subcontinent\n|headquarters = [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]\n|leader_title = President\n|leader_name = Charouck Arirachakaran\n|website = {{URL|http://www.seagfoffice.org/}}\n|remarks =\n}}\nThe '''Southeast Asian Games''', also known as the '''SEA Games''' ''(SEAG)'', is a biennial [[multi-sport event]] involving participants from the current 11 countries of [[Southeast Asia]]. The games is under regulation of the [[Southeast Asian Games Federation]] with supervision by the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) and the [[Olympic Council of Asia]].\n\n==History==\nThe Southeast Asian Games owes its origins to the '''''South East Asian Peninsular Games''''' or '''''SEAP Games'''''. On 22 May 1958, delegates from the countries in Southeast Asian Peninsula attending the [[1958 Asian Games|Asian Games]] in Tokyo, Japan had a meeting and agreed to establish a sport organisation. The SEAP Games was conceptualised by Luang Sukhum Nayaoradit, then Vice-President of the [[Thailand Olympic Committee]]. The proposed rationale was that a regional sports event will help promote co-operation, understanding and relations among countries in the Southeast Asian region.\n\nSix countries, Burma (now [[Myanmar]]), [[Kampuchea]] (now [[Cambodia]]), [[Laos]], [[Federation of Malaya|Malaya]] (now [[Malaysia]]), [[Thailand]] and [[Vietnam]] were the founding members. These countries agreed to hold the Games biennially in June 1959 and SEAP Games Federation Committee was formed thereafter.<ref name=\"charter\"/>\n\nThe first SEAP Games were held in [[Bangkok]] from 12\u201317 December 1959 comprising more than 527 athletes and officials from Thailand, Burma (now Myanmar), Malaya (now Malaysia), Singapore, South Vietnam and Laos participating in 12 sports.\n\nAt the 8th SEAP Games in 1975, the SEAP Federation considered the inclusion of [[Brunei]], [[Indonesia]] and the [[Philippines]]. These countries were formally admitted in 1977, the same year when SEAP Federation changed their name to the ''Southeast Asian Games Federation'' (SEAGF), and the games were known as the '''Southeast Asian Games'''. [[East Timor]] was admitted at the [[2003 Southeast Asian Games|22nd Southeast Asian Games]] in [[Vietnam]].\n\nThe [[2009 Southeast Asian Games]] was the first time Laos has ever hosted a Southeast Asian Games (Laos had previously declined hosting the 1965 Southeast Asian Peninsular Games citing financial difficulties). Running from 9\u201318 December, it has also commemorated the 50 years of the Southeast Asian Games, held in [[Vientiane]], [[Laos]].\n\n==Logo==\nThe Southeast Asian Games logo was introduced during the 1959 edition in Bangkok, depicting six rings that represent the six founding members and was used until the 1997 edition in Jakarta. The number of rings increased to 10 during the 1999 edition in Brunei to reflect the inclusion of Singapore which was admitted into the Southeast Asian Games Federation in 1961 and Brunei, Indonesia, and the Philippines which joined the organization in 1977. The number of rings was again increased to 11 during the 2011 games in Indonesia to reflect the federation's newest member, East Timor which was admitted in 2003.\n\n==Participating NOCs==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#E8E8E8\"\n! [[National Olympic Committee|NOC Names]] || Formal Names || Debuted  || [[International Olympic Committee|IOC]] code || Other codes used\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n| {{BRU}} || Nation of Brunei, the Abode of Peace ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1977 ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''BRU''' || BRN ([[International Organization for Standardization|ISO]])\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n| {{CAM}} || Kingdom of Cambodia ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1961 ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''CAM''' || KHM (1972\u20131976, ISO)\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n| {{INA}} || Republic of Indonesia ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1977 ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''INA''' || IHO (1952), IDN ([[FIFA]], ISO)\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n| {{LAO}} || Lao People's Democratic Republic ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1959 ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''LAO''' || \n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n| {{MAS}}|| Federation of Malaysia ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1959 ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''MAS''' || MAL (1952 \u2212 1988), MYS (ISO)\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n| {{MYA}} || Republic of the Union of Myanmar ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1959 ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''MYA''' || BIR (1948 \u2013 1988), MMR (ISO)\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n| {{PHI}} || Republic of the Philippines ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1977 ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''PHI''' || PHL (ISO)\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n| {{SGP}} || Republic of Singapore ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1959 ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''SGP''' || SIN (1959 \u2013 2016)\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n| {{THA}} || Kingdom of Thailand ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1959  ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''THA''' ||\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n| {{TLS}} || Democratic Republic of Timor-Leste ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | 2003 ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''TLS''' || [[Independent Olympians at the Olympic Games|IOA]] (2000)\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n| {{VIE}} || Socialist Republic of Vietnam ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1959 ||style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''VIE''' || VET (1964), VNM (1968\u20131976, ISO)\n|}\n\n==Host nations and cities==\n{{main|List of Southeast Asian Games host cities}}\n{{:List of Southeast Asian Games host cities}}\n{{List of Southeast Asian Games host nations and cities}}\n\nThe 1963 Southeast Asian Peninsular Games were canceled. As the designated host, [[Cambodia]] was not able to host the event due to unsettling in-country conditions, along with a disagreement with the [[International Amateur Athletic Federation]]. The 3rd SEAP Games then passed to [[Laos]] as hosts, but they begged off the 1965 event citing financial difficulties.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of the SEA Games |url=http://www.olympic.org.my/web/gamesrecords/sea/sea_history.htm |work=www.olympic.org.my |accessdate=26 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041217101809/http://www.olympic.org.my/web/gamesrecords/sea/sea_history.htm |archivedate=17 December 2004 }}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\n{{Main article|Southeast Asian Games sports}}\nAccording to the SEAGF Charter and Rules, a host nation must stage a minimum of 22 sports: the two compulsory sports from Category 1 (athletics and aquatics), in addition to a minimum of 14 sports from Category 2, and a maximum of 8 sports from Category 3 (shaded grey in the table below). Each sport shall not offer more than 5% of the total medal tally, except for athletics, aquatics, and shooting. For each sport and event to be included, a minimum of four countries must participate in it. Sports competed in the [[Olympic Games]] and [[Asian Games]] must be given priority.<ref name=\"charter\">{{cite web|url=http://voc.org.vn/Portals/0/2013-SEAG%20Charter.pdf |title=South East Asian Games Federation: Charter and Rules |publisher=SEAGF |date=30 May 2010 |accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayonline.com/sports/cool-addition-sea-games|title=A cool addition to the SEA Games|author=Ian De Cotta|publisher=Today Online|date=5 June 2015|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> \n\n{| cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em auto;\"\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! Sport || Years\n|-\n| [[Archery at the Southeast Asian Games|Archery]] || 1977\u20131997, since 2001\n|-\n|style=\"background: #D3D3D3;\" | [[Arnis]] || 1991, 2005, 2019\n|-\n|[[Athletics at the Southeast Asian Games|Athletics]] || All\n|-\n| [[Badminton at the Southeast Asian Games|Badminton]] || All\n|-\n|style=\"background: #D3D3D3;\" | [[Baseball at the Southeast Asian Games|Baseball]] || 2005\u20132007, 2011, since 2019\n|-\n| [[Basketball at the Southeast Asian Games|Basketball]] || 1979\u20132003, 2007, since 2011\n|-\n| [[Billiards and snooker at the Southeast Asian Games|Billiards and snooker]] || Since 1991\n|-\n