ondo]] || Since 1985\n|-\n| [[Tennis at the Southeast Asian Games|Tennis]] || 1959\u20132011, since 2015\n|-\n| style=\"background: #D3D3D3;\" | [[Traditional boat race at the Southeast Asian Games|Traditional boat race]] || 1993, 1997\u20131999, <br />2003\u20132007, 2011\u20132015\n|-\n| [[Triathlon at the Southeast Asian Games|Triathlon]] || 2005\u20132007, since 2015\n|-\n| [[Volleyball at the Southeast Asian Games|Volleyball]] || 1959\u20131997, since 2001\n|-\n| style=\"background: #D3D3D3;\" | [[Vovinam at the Southeast Asian Games|Vovinam]] || 2011\u20132013\n|-\n| [[Water polo at the Southeast Asian Games|Water polo]] || 1965\u20132017\n|-\n| [[Water skiing at the Southeast Asian Games|Water skiing]] || 1987, 1997, 2011, 2015\u20132017\n|-\n| [[Wakeboarding at the 2019 Southeast Asian Games|Wakeboarding]] || Since 2019\n|-\n| [[Weightlifting at the Southeast Asian Games|Weightlifting]] || 1959\u20131997, 2001\u20132013, since 2017\n|-\n| [[Wrestling at the Southeast Asian Games|Wrestling]] || 1987, 1997, 2003\u20132013, since 2019\n|-\n| [[Wushu at the Southeast Asian Games|Wushu]] || 1991\u20131993, 1997, since 2001\n|}\n|}\n\n==All-time medal table==\nCorrected after balancing the data of the [[Olympic Council of Asia]] and other archived sites which had kept the previous Southeast Asian Games medal tables. Some information from the aforementioned sites are missing, incorrect and or not updated.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ocasia.org/Game/NocsMedalCount.aspx?SYCXGjC0df+J2ChZBk5tvA== |title=South East Asian Games Medal Count |access-date=31 August 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.seagfoffice.org/ SEAP Games Federation]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/19980111005738/http://seagames.wasantara.net.id/medali59-95/medals.htm Medal Tally 1959-1995]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20081011071000/http://www.newsviews.info/sport09.html#sources Medal Tally]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20041217101809/http://www.olympic.org.my/web/gamesrecords/sea/sea_history.htm History of the SEA Games]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091204132925/http://www.laoseagames2009.com/v1/seagamesxseapxstat.aspx SEA Games previous medal table]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20011207141223/http://www.kl2001.com/index.html SEA Games members]</ref>\n\n{{Medals table\n | caption        = All-time Southeast Asian Games medal table{{ref|1|[1]}}\n | host           = \n | flag_template  = flagSEAGFteam\n | event          = \n | team           = NOC\n | gold_THA = 1885 | silver_THA = 1930 | bronze_THA = 1943\n | gold_INA = 1824| silver_INA = 1703 | bronze_INA = 1780\n | gold_MAS = 1303 | silver_MAS = 1273 | bronze_MAS = 1685 | note_MAS = {{ref|2|[2]}}\n | gold_PHI = 1067 | silver_PHI = 1193 | bronze_PHI = 1477\n | gold_SGP = 947 | silver_SGP = 1002 | bronze_SGP = 1363\n | gold_VIE = 928 | silver_VIE = 967 | bronze_VIE = 991 | note_VIE = {{ref|3|[3]}}\n | gold_MYA = 564 | silver_MYA = 741 | bronze_MYA = 992 | note_MYA = {{ref|4|[4]}}\n | gold_LAO = 69 | silver_LAO = 93 | bronze_LAO = 319\n | gold_CAM = 69 | silver_CAM = 115 | bronze_CAM = 258 | note_CAM = {{ref|5|[5]}}\n | gold_BRU = 14 | silver_BRU = 55 | bronze_BRU = 163\n | gold_TLS = 3 | silver_TLS = 6 | bronze_TLS = 26\n}}\n<small>\n*{{note|1|[1]}} - [[2017 Southeast Asian Games]] medal counts are not yet included in these medal standings due to ongoing doping cases during those games\n*{{note|2|[2]}} \u2013 Competed as Malaya in the inaugural games until 1961.\n*{{note|3|[3]}} \u2013 The Republic of Vietnam was dissolved in July 1976 when it merged with the [[North Vietnam|Democratic Republic of Vietnam]] (North Vietnam) to become the [[Vietnam|Socialist Republic of Vietnam]], also known as Vietnam. Therefore, the medal counts for this country are considered to be as until 1975. In the 1989 edition, a unified Vietnam rejoined the games with a new name and flag. Medals won by South Vietnam are already combined here. The [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) does not use codes for South Vietnam anymore after the unification with North Vietnam.\n*{{note|4|[4]}} \u2013 Competed as Burma until 1987.\n*{{note|5|[5]}} \u2013 Competed as Kampuchea, and Khmer Republic.</small>\n\n==List of multiple Southeast Asian Games medalists==\n{{Main|List of multiple Southeast Asian Games medalists}}\nVarious individuals have won multiple medals at the Games, including the preceding Southeast Asian Peninsular Games. \n\nAs of 2019, Singaporean swimmer [[Joscelin Yeo]] has won the most Southeast Asian Games medals with 55 (40 gold, 12 silver, 3 bronze). She reached this milestone during the [[2005 Southeast Asian Games|2005 Games]], overtaking the previous record of 39 gold medals set by another Singaporean swimmer [[Patricia Chan]].\n\n==Criticism==\nThe games is unique in that it has no official limits to the number of sports to be contested, and the range can be decided by the organizing host pending approval by the Southeast Asian Games Federation. Aside from core sports that must be featured, the host is free to drop or introduce other events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/2103469/southeast-asian-games-yet-win-gold-sporting-spirit|title=Southeast Asian Games yet to win gold for sporting spirit|agency=[[South China Morning Post]]|author=Pattharapong Rattanasevee |date=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nThis leeway has resulted in hosts maximizing their medal hauls by dropping sports disadvantageous to themselves relative to their peers and the introduction of obscure sports, often at short notice, thus preventing most other nations from building credible opponents. Examples of these include:\n\n* At the [[2001 Southeast Asian Games]], Malaysia introduced [[p\u00e9tanque]], and [[netball]].\n* At the [[2003 Southeast Asian Games]], Vietnam added [[fin swimming]] and [[Jianzi|shuttlecock]], and had the wushu offer 28 golds from 16 in 2001.\n* In the [[2005 Southeast Asian Games]], the [[Philippines]] added [[Eskrima|arnis]], a demonstration sport in 2003, with six sets of medals, and it won three golds. Also added were baseball, dancesport and softball.\n* At the [[2007 Southeast Asian Games]], [[Thailand]] added categories of [[sepak takraw]] and used a new kind of ball used by its athletes for a year but never used by other countries. [[Futsal]] was also added. Thailand won nearly all medals in the event.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sports |url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/en/sports/5317/sea-games-or-a-village-festival.html |title=VietNamNet - SEA Games or a village festival &#124; SEA Games or a village festival |publisher=English.vietnamnet.vn |date= |accessdate=2 June 2011}}</ref>\n* In the [[2011 Southeast Asian Games]], [[Indonesia]] dropped the team events in table tennis and shrunk the medals offered in shooting to just 14 golds from 19 in 2009 and 33 in 2007. At the same time, [[Contract bridge|bridge]], [[kenp\u014d]], [[paragliding]], [[vovinam]] and [[Sport climbing|wall climbing]] were introduced.\n* In the [[2013 Southeast Asian Games]], [[Myanmar]] introduced its indigenous sport [[Chinlone]]. The host won six of eight gold medals in the event. [[Sittuyin]], a traditional form of Burmese chess that other competing nations were unfamiliar with, was included as a traditional chess number along with common [[chess]] competition number.<ref name=\"PhnomPenhPost\">{{cite web | url=http://www.phnompenhpost.com/sport/cambodia-eye-record-medal-haul | title=Cambodia eye record medal haul | author=HS Manjunath | publisher=The Phnom Penh Post | date=10 December 2013 | accessdate=13 December 2013}}</ref>\n* In the [[2017 Southeast Asian Games]], Malaysia introduced [[cricket]], [[indoor hockey]] and three [[Winter Olympics]] sports, namely [[figure skating]], [[short track speed skating]] and [[ice hockey]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.redbull.com/my-en/6-new-sports-watch-2017-sea-games|title=4 new sports we can now watch in 2017 SEA Games|work=Red Bull|access-date=2017-08-29|language=en}}</ref>\n* In the [[2019 Southeast Asian Games]], the [[Philippines]] added [[Beach handball|beach handball]], [[Duathlon|duathlon]], [[Esports|e-sports]], [[Jujutsu|jiu-jitsu]], [[Kickboxing|kickboxing]], [[Kurash|kurash]], [[sambo (martial art)|sambo]], [[Skateboarding|skateboarding]], [[Surfing|surfing]] and [[Wakeboarding|wakeboarding]] and [[Modern Pentathlon]] in non-Olympic format.\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* Events of the [[Olympic Council of Asia|OCA]] (Continental)\n** [[Asian Games]]\n** [[Asian Winter Games]]\n** [[Asian Youth Games]]\n** [[Asian Beach Games]]\n** [[Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games]]\n* Events of the [[Olympic Council of Asia|OCA]] (Regional)\n** [[East Asian Games]]\n** [[East Asian Youth Games]]\n** [[Central Asian Games]]\n** [[South Asian Games]]\n** [[West Asian Games]]\n{{col-2}}\n\n* Events of the [[Asian Paralympic Committee|APC]] (Continental)\n** [[Asian Para Games]]\n** [[Asian Youth Para Games]]\n\n* Events of the [[Asian Paralympic Committee|APC]] (Regional)\n** [[ASEAN Para Games]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ocasia.org/Game/GamesL1.aspx?GPCode=8 Olympic Council of Asia Regional Hosting List]\n* [http://www.seagfoffice.org/ SEA Games Federation]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/19980111005738/http://seagames.wasantara.net.id/medali59-95/medals.htm Medal Tally 1959-1995]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081011071000/http://www.newsviews.info/sport09.html#sources Medal Tally]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041217101809/http://www.olympic.org.my/web/gamesrecords/sea/sea_history.htm History of the SEA Games]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091204132925/http://www.laoseagames2009.com/v1/seagamesxseapxstat.aspx SEA Games previous medal table]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20011207141223/http://www.kl2001.com/index.html SEA Games members]\n\n{{Southeast Asian Multi Sports Events}}\n{{Sports at the Southeast Asian Games}}\n{{Nations 